{"title_page": "Tontine", "text_new": "{{About|the financial instrument| the digital pensions company|Tontine Trust|the racehorse|Tontine (horse)|the Australian pillow manufacturer|Tontine Group}}\n{{confused|text = a [[dead pool]]}}\n[[File:Tontine Hotel sign, Ironbridge, UK.JPG|thumb|Tontine Hotel sign, [[Ironbridge]], Shropshire, UK]]\nA '''tontine''' (English pronunciation: {{IPAc-en|t|\u0252|n|t|i\u02d0|n}}) is an investment plan for raising capital, devised in the 17th century and relatively widespread in the 18th and 19th centuries. \n\nIt enables subscribers to share the risk of living a long life by combining features of a group [[Annuity (financial contracts)|annuity]] with a kind of mortality [[lottery]]. Each subscriber pays an agreed sum into the fund and thereafter receives a periodical payout. As members die, their payout entitlements devolve to the other participants, and so the value of each continuing payout increases. On the death of the last member, the scheme is wound up.<ref>Weir 1989, pp. 96, 102\u20133, 105.</ref>\n\nTontines are regulated in Europe under the Directive 2002/83/EC of the European Parliament<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/ALL/?uri=CELEX:32002L0083|title=EUR-Lex - 32002L0083 - EN - EUR-Lex|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2017-10-17}}</ref> and are still common in [[France]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/international/3363847/Property-in-France-Keep-it-in-la-famille-now-and-for-ever.html|title=Property in France: Keep it in la famille now and for ever|last=Ingram|first=Miranda|date=2008-08-29|access-date=2017-10-16|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThe new [[Pan-European Pension]] legislation coming into force in August 2020 contains provisions which specifically pave the way for a next-generation of pension products that abide by the \"tontine principle\".<ref name=\"meerten&hoog\">{{cite journal |last1=Meerten |first1=Hans van |last2=Hooghiemstra |first2=Sebastiaan Niels |title=PEPP \u2013 Towards a Harmonized European Legislative Framework for Personal Pensions |journal=SSRN |url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=2993991 |date=July 2017 }}</ref>\n\nQuestionable practices by U.S. life insurers in 1906 led to the [[Armstrong Investigation]] in the United States restricting some forms of tontines. Nevertheless, in March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that tontines were getting fresh consideration as a way for people to get steady retirement income.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/24/business/retirement/tontines-retirement-annuity.html?_r=0 |title=When Others Die, Tontine Investors Win |website=nytimes.com |date=2017-03-24 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe investment plan is named after [[Naples|Neapolitan]] banker [[Lorenzo de Tonti]], who is popularly credited with inventing it in [[France]] in 1653. In fact, he more probably merely modified existing Italian investment schemes,<ref>Jennings; Swanson; Trout (1988), p. 107</ref> while another precursor was a proposal put to the Senate of [[Lisbon]] by Nicolas Bourey in 1641.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McKeever|first=Kent|date=10 February 2017 |title=A Tontine before Lorenzo de Tonti's! The Lisbon Tontine Proposal of 1641 |url=https://news.law.fordham.edu/jcfl/2017/02/10/a-tontine-before-lorenzo-de-tontis-the-lisbon-tontine-proposal-of-1641/|journal=Fordham Journal of Corporate & Financial Law Blog|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Tonti put his proposal to the French royal government, but after consideration it was rejected by the [[Parlement|Parlement de Paris]].<ref name=\"eb1911\">{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Tontine|volume=27}}</ref> The first true tontine was therefore organised in the city of [[Kampen, Overijssel|Kampen]] in the Netherlands in 1670. The French finally established a state tontine in 1689<ref name=\"eb1911\" /> (though it was not described by that name because Tonti had died in disgrace, about five years earlier). The English government organised a tontine in 1693.<ref name=\"Milevsky\">Milevsky 2015.</ref> Nine further government tontines were organised in France down to 1759; four more in Britain down to 1789; and others in the Netherlands and some of the German states. Those in Britain were not fully subscribed, and in general the British schemes tended to be less popular and successful than their continental counterparts.<ref>Weir 1989, pp. 95\u2013124</ref>\n\nBy the end of the 18th century, the tontine had fallen out of favour as a revenue-raising instrument with governments, but smaller-scale and less formal tontines continued to be arranged between individuals or to raise funds for specific projects throughout the 19th century, and, in modified form, to the present day.<ref name=nytimes/>\n\n==Concept==\nEach investor pays a sum into the tontine. Each investor then receives annual [[interest]] on the [[Financial capital|capital]] invested. As each investor dies, his or her share is reallocated among the surviving investors. This process continues until the death of the final investor, when the scheme is wound up. Each subscriber receives only interest; the capital is never paid back.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\">Weir 1989, pp. 103\u2013104</ref>\n\nStrictly speaking, the transaction involves four different roles:<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\n# the government or corporate body which organizes the scheme, receives the loans and manages the capital\n# the subscribers who provide the capital\n# the shareholders who receive the annual interest\n# the nominees on whose lives the contracts are contingent\n\nIn most 18th- and 19th-century schemes, parties 2 to 4 were the same individuals; but in a significant minority of schemes each initial subscriber-shareholder was permitted to invest in the name of another party (generally one of his or her own children), who would inherit that share on the subscriber's death.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\nBecause younger nominees clearly had a longer life expectancy, the 17th- and 18th-century tontines were normally divided into several \"classes\" by age (typically in bands of 5, 7 or 10 years): each class effectively formed a separate tontine, with the shares of deceased members devolving to fellow-nominees within the same class.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\nIn a later variation, the capital devolves upon the last survivor, thus dissolving the trust and potentially making the survivor very wealthy.{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}} This version has often provided the plot device for mysteries and detective stories.\n\n==Patent==\n[[File:Dousset 1792.png|thumb|right|First page of Dousset 1792 French patent for a tontine]][[Business method patent|Financial inventions were patentable]] under French law from January 1791 until September 1792.  In June 1792 a patent was issued to inventor F. P. Dousset for a new type of tontine in combination with a [[lottery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cEYFAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA559#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=Description des machines et proc\u00e9d\u00e9s sp\u00e9cifi\u00e9s dans les brevets d'invention, publ. par C.P. Molard. [With] Table g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des vingt premiers volumes. [Continued as] Description des machines ... pour lesquels des brevets d'invention ont \u00e9t\u00e9 pris sous le r\u00e9gime de la loi du 5 juillet 1844|first=France min du|last=commerce|date=30 April 2018|publisher=|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Uses and abuses==\n[[Louis XIV]] first made use of tontines in 1689 to fund military operations when he could not otherwise raise the money. The initial subscribers each put in 300 [[French livre|livres]] and, unlike most later schemes, this one was run honestly; the last survivor, a widow named Charlotte Barbier, who died in 1726 at the age of 96, received 73,000 livres in her last payment.<ref>Coudy 1957</ref><ref>Jennings and Trout 1982.</ref><ref name=\"Weir89\">Weir 1989.</ref> The English government first issued tontines in 1693 to fund a war against France, part of the [[Nine Years' War]].<ref name=\"Milevsky\"/><ref name=\"Weir89\"/>\n\nTontines soon caused financial problems for their issuing governments, as the organisers tended to underestimate the [[longevity]] of the population. At first, tontine holders included men and women of all ages. However, by the mid-18th century, investors were beginning to understand how to [[Gaming the system|game the system]], and it became increasingly common to buy tontine shares for young children, especially for girls around the age of 5 (since girls lived longer than boys, and by which age they were less at risk of infant mortality). This created the possibility of significant returns for the shareholders, with significant losses for the organizers. As a result, tontine schemes were eventually abandoned, and by the mid-1850s tontines had been replaced by other investment vehicles, such as \"[[penny policy|penny policies]]\", a predecessor of the 20th-century [[pension]] scheme.{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}}<!-- the previous paragraph mentions dishonestly-run tontines; there should be a discussion of those, too, and that phenomenon's role in the move to prohibit the tontine.-->\n\nA property development tontine, The Victoria Park Company, was at the heart of the notable case of ''[[Foss v Harbottle]]'' in mid-19th-century [[England]].{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}}\n\n==Projects funded by tontines==\n[[File:Tontine coffee house.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The [[Tontine Coffee House]] (at left) on [[Wall Street]], [[New York City]]]]\nTontines were often used to raise funds for private or [[public works]] projects.<ref>Green 2019.</ref> These sometimes contained the word \"tontine\" in their name.\n\nSome notable tontine-funded projects included:\n*[[Richmond Bridge, London|Richmond Bridge]], across the [[River Thames]] west of London, was financed using a tontine in 1774.\n*The Tontine Hotel in [[Ironbridge]], Shropshire, stands prominently at one end of the [[The Iron Bridge|Iron Bridge]] from which the town takes its name: it was built in 1780\u201384 by the proprietors of the bridge to accommodate tourists who came to view this wonder of the industrial age.\n*The [[Glasgow Cross|Tontine Hotel and Assembly Rooms]], [[Glasgow]], were funded through two tontine of 1781 and 1796.\n*The [[Tontine Coffee House]] on [[Wall Street]] in [[New York City]], built in 1792, was the first home of the [[New York Stock Exchange]].\n*The first [[Freemasons' Hall, London]]. Subscribers were able to nominate someone other than themselves as the person on whose life the share was staked.  On the subscriber's death they could leave their share to that person, or to anyone else. The scheme raised \u00a35,000, but cost \u00a321,750 in interest over its 87-year life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mqmagazine.co.uk/issue-19/p-52.php |title=MQ Magazine |volume=19 |publisher=United Grand Lodge of England}}</ref>\n*The Tontine Hotel, [[Greenock]], [[Inverclyde]], [[Scotland]], was built in 1803.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.historic-scotland.gov.uk/pls/htmldb/f?p=2200:15:0::::BUILDING:34078|title=Tontine Hotel, 5 Ardgowan Square: Listed Building Report |publisher=Historic Scotland}}</ref>\n*The Cleveland Tontine hotel, near [[Ingleby Arncliffe]], North Yorkshire, originally a [[coaching inn]] on the [[Yarm]] to [[Thirsk]] [[Turnpike trusts|turnpike road]], was financed using a tontine in 1804.<ref>{{cite web |title=About The Tontine: History of The Tontine |publisher=The Cleveland Tontine |url=https://www.theclevelandtontine.com/about/ |accessdate=28 February 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Tontine pensions in the US: 1868\u20131906==\nTontines became associated with life insurance in the United States in 1868 when [[Henry Baldwin Hyde]] of the [[AXA Equitable Life Insurance Company|Equitable Life Assurance Society]] introduced them as a means of selling more life insurance and meeting the demands of competition. Over the next four decades, the Equitable and its imitators sold approximately 9 million policies \u2013 two-thirds of the nation's outstanding insurance contracts. During the [[Panic of 1873]] many life insurance companies went out of business as deteriorating financial conditions created solvency problems: those that survived had all offered tontines.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yang |first1=Tony |date=2009 |page=5 |title=The Performance of Life Insurance Companies: 1860\u20131905 |url=http://www.americasmutualbanks.com/images/0714_YangPaper.pdf }}</ref> However, the contracts included an obligation to maintain monthly payments, and as a result spawned large numbers of policy owners whose life savings were wiped out by a single missed payment. The profits produced by the tontines' deferred payout structures proved tempting for the issuers \u2013 especially the profligate [[James Hazen Hyde|James Hyde]]. As the funds in the investment account accumulated, they found their way into directors' and agents' pockets, and also into the hands of judges and legislators, who reciprocated with prejudicial judgments and laws.<ref>{{cite journal |first=William J. |last=Bernstein |title=King William's Tontine: Why the Retirement Annuity of the Future Should Resemble Its Past (a review) |journal=Financial Analysts Journal |publisher=CFA Institute |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=2015 |url=https://www.cfapubs.org/doi/full/10.2469/br.v10.n1.17 |accessdate=11 May 2018 |doi=10.2469/br.v10.n1.17 |doi-broken-date=2019-12-16 }}</ref> \n\nFinally, in 1905, the [[Armstrong Investigation]] was set up to enquire into the selling of tontines. It resulted in the banning of the continued sale of those tontines which contained toxic clauses for consumers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moss |first1=David |first2=Eugene |last2=Kintgen |title=The Armstrong Investigation |journal=Harvard Business School Case Collection |volume=708-034 |origyear=January 2008 |date=January 2009 |url=https://www.hbs.edu/faculty/Pages/item.aspx?num=35348 |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism from competitors==\nWhen Equitable Life Assurance was establishing its business in Australia in the 1880s, an actuary of the [[AMP Limited|Australian Mutual Provident Society]] criticised tontine insurance, calling it \"an immoral contract\" which \"put a premium on murder\".<ref>Buley 1967, p. 291.</ref> In New Zealand at the time, another of the chief critics of tontines had been the government, which also issued its own insurance.<ref>Buley 1967, p. 472.</ref>\n\n==Modern regulation==\nUntil recently, the First Life Directive of the European Union specified tontines as a class of insurance business however the new [[Pan-European Pension]] legislation coming into force in August 2020 specifically paves the way for other types of financial service providers to create new pension products that abide by the \"tontine principle\".<ref name=\"meerten&hoog\"/>\n\nIn most places in the United States using tontines to raise capital or obtain lifetime income is consistently upheld as being legal; however, outdated legislation in two states has fostered the incorrect perception that selling tontines in the broader U.S. is illegal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tardi |first1=Carla |title=Tontine |url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/tontine.asp |website=Investopedia}}</ref>\n\n==Tontine pensions in the 21st Century==\nIn 2015, John Barry Forman and Michael J. Sabin, using modern actuarial techniques to calculate fair transfer payments when participants are of different ages and have made different contributions, proposed a new structure of [[pension]] plan on the tontine model, through which large employers could provide retirement income for their employees. They argued that tontine pensions would have two major advantages over traditional pensions, as they would always be fully funded, and the plan sponsor would not be required to bear the investment and actuarial risks.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.pennlawreview.com/print/163-U-Pa-L-Rev-755.pdf |first1=John Barry |last1=Forman |first2= Michael J. |last2=Sabin |title=Tontine Pensions |journal=[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]] |volume=163 |issue=3 |year=2015 |pages=755\u2013831 }}</ref> Similar arguments were put forward in the same year by [[Moshe Milevsky]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=King William's Tontine: Why the Retirement Annuity of the Future Should Resemble its Past|last=Milevsky|first=Moshe A.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1107076129|location=|pages=170\u201397}}</ref> In March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that tontines were getting fresh consideration as a way for people to get steady retirement income.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Dean McClelland, Richard Fullmer and Jon Matonis and others published a whitepaper to deliver secure low cost Tontine Pensions based loosely upon the Forman, Sabin and Milevsky format under the brand [[Tontine Trust]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tontine.com/whitepaper-nt/TontineTrust.Non-Technical.Whitepaper.(V1.01D).pdf|title=Tontine Trust - Retirement Planning for the 21st Century|last=McClelland|first=Dean|date=November 15, 2017|website=Tontine.com}}</ref>  In 2018, Richard K. Fullmer and Michael J. Sabin expanded on the ideas presented in Forman and Sabin (2015) by showing that participants in an actuarially fair tontine need not be confined to a common investment portfolio or to a common payout method. Their paper introduced the concept of individual tontine accounts (ITAs), which they envisioned as complementary to individual retirement account (IRAs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=3217551|title=Individual Tontine Accounts|last=Fullmer|first=Richard K.|last2=Sabin|first2=Michael J.|date=July 21, 2018|website=SSRN}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[CFA Institute]] Research Foundation published a research brief titled ''Tontines: A Practitioner's Guide to Mortality-Pooled Investments'' noting that \"the study of fair tontine design is a specialty all its own\u2014one that has emerged only recently.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.cfainstitute.org/-/media/documents/article/rf-brief/fullmer-tontines-rf-brief.ashx|title=Tontines: A Practitioner's Guide to Mortality-Pooled Investments|last=Fullmer|first=Richard K.|publisher=CFA Institute Research Foundation|year=2019|isbn=978-1-944960-75-9|location=|pages=}}</ref> Fullmer and Sabin showed that it is possible to engineer payouts within a tontine structure that are immune to interest rate and reinvestment risk.<ref>Fullmer, Richard K. and Sabin, Michael J. (April 16, 2019). [https://ssrn.com/abstract=3373251 Tontine Bond Ladders]. Available at SSRN.</ref>\n\nSeveral new pension architectures have been designed or deployed which partially or fully utilise the tontine risk-sharing structure including:\n*Defined Ambition pensions\n*Target Benefit pensions\n*Collective Defined Contribution pensions or [[CDC Pensions]]\n\n==Variant uses of the term==\nIn French-speaking cultures, particularly in [[Developing country|developing countries]], the meaning of the term \"tontine\" has broadened to encompass a wider range of semi-formal group savings and [[microcredit]] schemes. The crucial difference between these and tontines in the traditional sense is that benefits do not depend on the deaths of other members.\n\nIn the UK during the mid-20th century, the term was applied to communal Christmas saving schemes, with participants making regular payments of an agreed sum through the year, which would be withdrawn shortly before Christmas to fund gifts and festivities.<ref>For a description and images of a contribution card, see {{cite web |title=Rhostyllen: a history through pictures |url=http://rhostyllen.info/misc.html |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAs a type of [[Rotating Savings and Credit Association|rotating savings and credit association]] (ROSCA), tontines are well established as a savings instrument in central Africa, and in this case function as savings clubs in which each member makes regular payments and is lent the [[wiktionary:kitty#noun|kitty]] in turn. They are wound up after each cycle of loans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ecole.org/seminaires/FS3/SEM105/VC190603-ENG.pdf |title=Using tontines to run the economy |first=Alain |last=Henry |publisher=l'\u00c9cole de Paris du management |date=June 19, 2003}}</ref> In West Africa, \"tontines\" \u2013 often consisting of mainly women \u2013 are an example of economic, social and cultural solidarity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dandc.eu/en/article/self-organised-savings-communities-tontines-are-example-economic-social-and-cultural |title=Flexible and disciplined |first=Eva-Maria |last=Bruchhaus |publisher=D+C, Development and Cooperation |date=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nInformal group savings and loan associations are also traditional in many east Asian societies, and under the name of tontines are found in [[Cambodia]], and among emigrant Cambodian communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cambodia.org.nz/Tontine.htm |title=Tontine: an alternative financial instrument in Cambodian communities |first=Man Hau |last=Liev |publisher=12th NZASIA Conference |date=November 26\u201329, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Singapore]], the Chit Funds Act of 1971<ref>{{cite web |title=Chit Funds Act |work=Singapore Statutes Online |origyear=1971 |year=2013 |url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Act/CFA1971 |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref> defines the application of legislation to the operation of [[chit fund]]s, which were also known colloquially as tontines but which operated on a different principle more commonly known as a ROSCA ([[Rotating Savings and Credit Association]]).\n \nIn [[Malaysia]], chit funds are primarily known as \"kootu funds\", which again are ROSCAs and which are defined under the ''Kootu Funds (Prohibition) Act 1971'' as \n\"...a scheme or arrangement variously known as a kootu, cheetu, chit fund, hwei, tontine or otherwise whereby the participants subscribe periodically or otherwise to a common fund and such common fund is put up for sale or payment to the participants by auction, tender, bid, ballot or otherwise...\" <ref>{{cite web |title=Kootu Funds (Prohibition) Act 1971 |work=Commonwealth Legal Information Institute |year=1971 |url=http://www.commonlii.org/my/legis/consol_act/kfa1971281/ |accessdate=27 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nTontines have been featured as plot devices in many fictional stories, movies and television programs, including:\n*''La Tontine'' (1708), a comic play by [[Alain-Ren\u00e9 Lesage]]. A physician, hoping to raise the funds to give his daughter a dowry, buys a tontine on the life of an elderly peasant, who he then strives to keep alive.\n*''The Great Tontine'' (1881), is a novel by [[Henry Hawley Smart|Hawley Smart]].\n*''[[The Wrong Box (novel)|The Wrong Box]]'' (1889), is a comic novel by [[Robert Louis Stevenson]] and [[Lloyd Osbourne]]. The plot revolves around a tontine originally taken out for some wealthy English children, and the resulting shenanigans as younger family members of the two final survivors vie to secure the final payout. The book was adapted as a [[The Wrong Box|film]], produced and directed by [[Bryan Forbes]], (1966).\n*''The Secret Tontine'' (1912), is an atmospheric faux-gothic novel by [[Robert Murray Gilchrist]], set in the [[Derbyshire]] [[Peak District]] during a snowy winter in the late 19th century. The plot involves the potential beneficiaries of a covert tontine, and their scheme to murder their ignorant rivals. \n*[[Lillian de la Torre]]'s short story \"The Tontine Curse\" (1948) features mysterious deaths related to a tontine in 1779, being investigated by [[Samuel Johnson]].\n*''The Tontine'' (1955), a novel by [[Thomas B. Costain]], illustrated by [[Herbert Ryman]], is set in nineteenth-century England and tells a story centered around the fictional \"Waterloo Tontine\", established to benefit veterans of the Napoleonic wars. Among other plot twists, shareholders hire an actor to impersonate a dead nominee, and conspire to murder another member.\n*In ''[[4.50 from Paddington]]'' (1957), a [[Miss Marple]] murder mystery by [[Agatha Christie]], the plot revolves around the will of a wealthy industrialist, which establishes a [[Settlement (trust)|settlement]] under which his estate is divided in trust among his grandchildren, the final survivor to inherit the whole. The settlement is described, inaccurately, as a tontine. \n*''[[Something Fishy]]'' (1957), a novel by [[P. G. Wodehouse]], features a so-called tontine under which the investors' sons stand to gain from marrying late.\n* In the U.S. television series ''[[The Wild Wild West]]'', Episode 16 of Season Two (1966\u201367) \u2013 \"The Night of the Tottering Tontine\" \u2013 finds James West and Artemus Gordon protecting a man who is a member of a tontine whose members are being murdered one by another.\n*\"Old Soldiers,\" an eighth-season episode of the television series ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', focuses on a tontine set up among Colonel Potter and several of his Army buddies from [[World War I]]. While taking shelter in a ch\u00e2teau during an artillery barrage, they had found a cache of brandy and drank all but one bottle, which they set aside for the last survivor. After the only other surviving member dies, Potter receives the bottle in the mail and shares it with his staff, drinking first to his departed friends and then to the new ones he has made at the 4077th.\n*In the ''[[Barney Miller]]'' episode \"The Tontine\" (1982), one of the last two surviving family members who invested in the tontine attempts to kill himself so that the other can have the money before growing too old to enjoy it.\n* In ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Raging Abe Simpson and His Grumbling Grandson in \"The Curse of the Flying Hellfish\"]]\" (1996), [[Grampa Simpson]] and [[Mr. Burns]] are the final survivors of a tontine to determine ownership of art looted during [[World War II]]. Grampa eventually kicks Burns out of the tontine for trying to kill him, but before he and Bart can do anything with the art, a descendant of the original owner shows up to claim it.\n*In [[S. L. Viehl]]'s science fiction multi-volume novel ''Stardoc'' (2000), the title character is accused of spreading a plague to several colony worlds, on one of which the colonists had established a tontine. The sole survivor, a little girl, consequently becomes so wealthy that in the second book of the series \u2013 ''Beyond Varallan'' (2000) \u2013 she buys the bank behind the colonies to free the Stardoc from the debt she now owes.\n*The 2001 comedy film ''[[Tomcats (2001 film)|Tomcats]]'' features a variation on a tontine where the last investor to get married gets the full amount of the invested funds.\n* In the ''[[Archer (2009 TV series)|Archer]]'' episode \"The Double Deuce\" (2011), Archer's [[valet]] Woodhouse is revealed as one of three final survivors of a group of World War I [[Royal Flying Corps]] squadron mates who each put [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]50 into an interest-bearing account, now worth nearly a million [[United States dollar|dollars]]. The office workers at ISIS HQ, realizing that a new tontine could capitalize on the high mortality rate of field agents, begin persuading people to join.\n* The ''[[Diagnosis: Murder]]'' episode \"Being of Sound Mind\" (Season 8 Episode 16) features a tontine as a motive for murder.\n*The ''[[The Brokenwood Mysteries|Brokenwood Mysteries]]'' episode \"Tontine\" (Season 5 Episode 3) centres on a tontine.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Buley|first=R. Carlyle|title=The Equitable Life Assurance Society of the United States 1859\u20131964|date=1967|publisher=Appleton-Century-Crofts|location=New York}}\n*{{cite book |first=Geoffrey |last=Clark |title=Betting on Lives: the culture of life insurance in England, 1695\u20131775 |location=Manchester |publisher=Manchester University Press |year=1999 |isbn=9780719056758 }} \n*{{Cite journal |first=Julien |last=Coudy |title=La Tontine royal sous le r\u00e8gne de Louis XIV |journal=Revue historique de droit fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9tranger |volume=4th ser. 35 |year=1957 |pages=128\u201333 |language=fr}}\n*{{Cite journal |first=John |last=Dunkley |title=Bourbons on the Rocks: tontines and early public lotteries in France |journal=Journal for Eighteenth-Century Studies |volume=30 |issue=3 |year=2007 |pages=309\u201323 |doi=10.1111/j.1754-0208.2007.tb00338.x}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Gallais Hamonno |first1=Georges |last2=Berthon |first2=Jean |title=Les emprunts tontiniers de l'Ancien R\u00e9gime: un exemple d'ing\u00e9nierie financi\u00e8re au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle |location=Paris |year=2008 |language=fr}}\n*{{cite journal|first=David R. |last=Green |title=Tontines, annuities and civic improvements in Georgian Britain |journal=Urban History |volume=46 |issue=4 |year=2019 |pages=649\u201394 |doi=10.1017/s0963926818000743 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Trout |first2=Andrew P. |title=The Tontine: fact and fiction |journal=Journal of European Economic History |volume=5 |year=1976 |pages=663\u201370 }}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Trout |first2=Andrew P. |title=The Tontine: from the reign of Louis XIV to the French Revolutionary era |location=Homewood, IL |year=1982 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Swanson |first2=Donald F. |last3=Trout |first3=Andrew P. |title=Alexander Hamilton's tontine proposal |journal=William and Mary Quarterly |series=3rd ser. |volume=45 |issue=1 |year=1988 |pages=107\u2013115 |jstor=1922216|doi=10.2307/1922216 }}\n*{{Cite journal |url=http://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1108&context=jcfl&sei-redir=1#search=%22fordham%20tontines%22 |first=Kent |last=McKeever |title=A Short History of Tontines |journal=[[Fordham Journal of Corporate & Financial Law]] |volume=15 |issue=2 |year=2011 |pages=491\u2013521}}\n*{{cite book |last=Milevsky |first=Moshe A. |authorlink=Moshe Milevsky |title=King William's Tontine: why the retirement annuity of the future should resemble its past |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |year=2015 |isbn=978-110-707612-9}}\n*{{Cite journal |first=David R. |last=Weir |title=Tontines, Public Finance, and Revolution in France and England, 1688\u20131789 |journal=Journal of Economic History |volume=49 |year=1989 |pages=95\u2013124 |doi=10.1017/s002205070000735x|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/6b6216730f9bb206697414ac38327061feb3673d }}\n*{{Cite book|author=Wyler, Julius |title=Die Tontinen in Frankreich |location=Munich and Leipzig |year=1916 |language=de}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|tontine}}\n*[[wikisource:The Story of Life Insurance/Chapter IV|\"The Great Tontine Gamble\"]], one of a series of articles by [[Burton J. Hendrick]] appearing in ''[[McClure's Magazine]]'' in 1906\n*[http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a3_172.html ''The Straight Dope'': \"What's with tontines, the odd annuities in which you benefit when others die?\"]\n*[http://www.cato.org/pubs/regulation/regv32n4/v32n4-4.pdf Baker et al. (Winter 2009-2010) \"Tontines for the Young Invincibles\", ''Regulation'']\n*[https://www.forbes.com/sites/pensionresearchcouncil/2018/01/30/fintechs-answer-to-the-global-retirement-crisis/#586b0cd31ff3 \"Forbes  Pensions Research Council (Jan 18, 2018) \"Fintech's Answer To The Global Retirement Crisis\"]\n\n{{Economic history of the Netherlands}}\n\n[[Category:Investment]]\n[[Category:Informal finance]]\n[[Category:1653 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:17th-century introductions]]\n[[Category:Economic history of the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the financial instrument| the digital pensions company|Tontine Trust|the racehorse|Tontine (horse)|the Australian pillow manufacturer|Tontine Group}}\n{{confused|text = a [[dead pool]]}}\n[[File:Tontine Hotel sign, Ironbridge, UK.JPG|thumb|Tontine Hotel sign, [[Ironbridge]], Shropshire, UK]]\nA '''tontine''' (English pronunciation: {{IPAc-en|t|\u0252|n|t|i\u02d0|n}}) is an investment plan for raising capital, devised in the 17th century and relatively widespread in the 18th and 19th centuries. \n\nIt enables subscribers to share the risk of living a long life by combining features of a group [[Annuity (financial contracts)|annuity]] with a kind of mortality [[lottery]]. Each subscriber pays an agreed sum into the fund and thereafter receives a periodical payout. As members die, their payout entitlements devolve to the other participants, and so the value of each continuing payout increases. On the death of the last member, the scheme is wound up.<ref>Weir 1989, pp. 96, 102\u20133, 105.</ref>\n\nTontines are regulated in Europe under the Directive 2002/83/EC of the European Parliament<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/ALL/?uri=CELEX:32002L0083|title=EUR-Lex - 32002L0083 - EN - EUR-Lex|website=eur-lex.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2017-10-17}}</ref> and are still common in [[France]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/international/3363847/Property-in-France-Keep-it-in-la-famille-now-and-for-ever.html|title=Property in France: Keep it in la famille now and for ever|last=Ingram|first=Miranda|date=2008-08-29|access-date=2017-10-16|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThe new [[Pan-European Pension]] legislation coming into force in August 2020 contains provisions which specifically pave the way for a next-generation of pension products that abide by the \"tontine principle\".<ref name=\"meerten&hoog\">{{cite journal |last1=Meerten |first1=Hans van |last2=Hooghiemstra |first2=Sebastiaan Niels |title=PEPP \u2013 Towards a Harmonized European Legislative Framework for Personal Pensions |journal=SSRN |url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=2993991 |date=July 2017 }}</ref>\n\nQuestionable practices by U.S. life insurers in 1906 led to the [[Armstrong Investigation]] in the United States restricting some forms of tontines. Nevertheless, in March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that tontines were getting fresh consideration as a way for people to get steady retirement income.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/24/business/retirement/tontines-retirement-annuity.html?_r=0 |title=When Others Die, Tontine Investors Win |website=nytimes.com |date=2017-03-24 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe investment plan is named after [[Naples|Neapolitan]] banker [[Lorenzo de Tonti]], who is popularly credited with inventing it in [[France]] in 1653. In fact, he more probably merely modified existing Italian investment schemes,<ref>Jennings; Swanson; Trout (1988), p. 107</ref> while another precursor was a proposal put to the Senate of [[Lisbon]] by Nicolas Bourey in 1641.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McKeever|first=Kent|date=10 February 2017 |title=A Tontine before Lorenzo de Tonti's! The Lisbon Tontine Proposal of 1641 |url=https://news.law.fordham.edu/jcfl/2017/02/10/a-tontine-before-lorenzo-de-tontis-the-lisbon-tontine-proposal-of-1641/|journal=Fordham Journal of Corporate & Financial Law Blog|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Tonti put his proposal to the French royal government, but after consideration it was rejected by the [[Parlement|Parlement de Paris]].<ref name=\"eb1911\">{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Tontine|volume=27}}</ref> The first true tontine was therefore organised in the city of [[Kampen, Overijssel|Kampen]] in the Netherlands in 1670. The French finally established a state tontine in 1689<ref name=\"eb1911\" /> (though it was not described by that name because Tonti had died in disgrace, about five years earlier). The English government organised a tontine in 1693.<ref name=\"Milevsky\">Milevsky 2015.</ref> Nine further government tontines were organised in France down to 1759; four more in Britain down to 1789; and others in the Netherlands and some of the German states. Those in Britain were not fully subscribed, and in general the British schemes tended to be less popular and successful than their continental counterparts.<ref>Weir 1989, pp. 95\u2013124</ref>\n\nBy the end of the 18th century, the tontine had fallen out of favour as a revenue-raising instrument with governments, but smaller-scale and less formal tontines continued to be arranged between individuals or to raise funds for specific projects throughout the 19th century, and, in modified form, to the present day.<ref name=nytimes/>\n\n==Concept==\nEach investor pays a sum into the tontine. Each investor then receives annual [[interest]] on the [[Financial capital|capital]] invested. As each investor dies, his or her share is reallocated among the surviving investors. This process continues until the death of the final investor, when the scheme is wound up. Each subscriber receives only interest; the capital is never paid back.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\">Weir 1989, pp. 103\u2013104</ref>\n\nStrictly speaking, the transaction involves four different roles:<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\n# the government or corporate body which organizes the scheme, receives the loans and manages the capital\n# the subscribers who provide the capital\n# the shareholders who receive the annual interest\n# the nominees on whose lives the contracts are contingent\n\nIn most 18th- and 19th-century schemes, parties 2 to 4 were the same individuals; but in a significant minority of schemes each initial subscriber-shareholder was permitted to invest in the name of another party (generally one of his or her own children), who would inherit that share on the subscriber's death.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\nBecause younger nominees clearly had a longer life expectancy, the 17th- and 18th-century tontines were normally divided into several \"classes\" by age (typically in bands of 5, 7 or 10 years): each class effectively formed a separate tontine, with the shares of deceased members devolving to fellow-nominees within the same class.<ref name=\"Weir103-4\"/>\n\nIn a later variation, the capital devolves upon the last survivor, thus dissolving the trust and potentially making the survivor very wealthy.{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}} This version has often provided the plot device for mysteries and detective stories.\n\n==Patent==\n[[File:Dousset 1792.png|thumb|right|First page of Dousset 1792 French patent for a tontine]][[Business method patent|Financial inventions were patentable]] under French law from January 1791 until September 1792.  In June 1792 a patent was issued to inventor F. P. Dousset for a new type of tontine in combination with a [[lottery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cEYFAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA559#v=onepage&q=&f=false|title=Description des machines et proc\u00e9d\u00e9s sp\u00e9cifi\u00e9s dans les brevets d'invention, publ. par C.P. Molard. [With] Table g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des vingt premiers volumes. [Continued as] Description des machines ... pour lesquels des brevets d'invention ont \u00e9t\u00e9 pris sous le r\u00e9gime de la loi du 5 juillet 1844|first=France min du|last=commerce|date=30 April 2018|publisher=|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Uses and abuses==\n[[Louis XIV]] first made use of tontines in 1689 to fund military operations when he could not otherwise raise the money. The initial subscribers each put in 300 [[French livre|livres]] and, unlike most later schemes, this one was run honestly; the last survivor, a widow named Charlotte Barbier, who died in 1726 at the age of 96, received 73,000 livres in her last payment.<ref>Coudy 1957</ref><ref>Jennings and Trout 1982.</ref><ref name=\"Weir89\">Weir 1989.</ref> The English government first issued tontines in 1693 to fund a war against France, part of the [[Nine Years' War]].<ref name=\"Milevsky\"/><ref name=\"Weir89\"/>\n\nTontines soon caused financial problems for their issuing governments, as the organisers tended to underestimate the [[longevity]] of the population. At first, tontine holders included men and women of all ages. However, by the mid-18th century, investors were beginning to understand how to [[Gaming the system|game the system]], and it became increasingly common to buy tontine shares for young children, especially for girls around the age of 5 (since girls lived longer than boys, and by which age they were less at risk of infant mortality). This created the possibility of significant returns for the shareholders, with significant losses for the organizers. As a result, tontine schemes were eventually abandoned, and by the mid-1850s tontines had been replaced by other investment vehicles, such as \"[[penny policy|penny policies]]\", a predecessor of the 20th-century [[pension]] scheme.{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}}<!-- the previous paragraph mentions dishonestly-run tontines; there should be a discussion of those, too, and that phenomenon's role in the move to prohibit the tontine.-->\n\nA property development tontine, The Victoria Park Company, was at the heart of the notable case of ''[[Foss v Harbottle]]'' in mid-19th-century [[England]].{{Citation needed|date = October 2016}}\n\n==Projects funded by tontines==\n[[File:Tontine coffee house.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The [[Tontine Coffee House]] (at left) on [[Wall Street]], [[New York City]]]]\nTontines were often used to raise funds for private or [[public works]] projects.<ref>Green 2019.</ref> These sometimes contained the word \"tontine\" in their name.\n\nSome notable tontine-funded projects included:\n*[[Richmond Bridge, London|Richmond Bridge]], across the [[River Thames]] west of London, was financed using a tontine in 1774.\n*The Tontine Hotel in [[Ironbridge]], Shropshire, stands prominently at one end of the [[The Iron Bridge|Iron Bridge]] from which the town takes its name: it was built in 1780\u201384 by the proprietors of the bridge to accommodate tourists who came to view this wonder of the industrial age.\n*The [[Glasgow Cross|Tontine Hotel and Assembly Rooms]], [[Glasgow]], were funded through two tontine of 1781 and 1796.\n*The [[Tontine Coffee House]] on [[Wall Street]] in [[New York City]], built in 1792, was the first home of the [[New York Stock Exchange]].\n*The first [[Freemasons' Hall, London]]. Subscribers were able to nominate someone other than themselves as the person on whose life the share was staked.  On the subscriber's death they could leave their share to that person, or to anyone else. The scheme raised \u00a35,000, but cost \u00a321,750 in interest over its 87-year life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mqmagazine.co.uk/issue-19/p-52.php |title=MQ Magazine |volume=19 |publisher=United Grand Lodge of England}}</ref>\n*The Tontine Hotel, [[Greenock]], [[Inverclyde]], [[Scotland]], was built in 1803.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.historic-scotland.gov.uk/pls/htmldb/f?p=2200:15:0::::BUILDING:34078|title=Tontine Hotel, 5 Ardgowan Square: Listed Building Report |publisher=Historic Scotland}}</ref>\n*The Cleveland Tontine hotel, near [[Ingleby Arncliffe]], North Yorkshire, originally a [[coaching inn]] on the [[Yarm]] to [[Thirsk]] [[Turnpike trusts|turnpike road]], was financed using a tontine in 1804.<ref>{{cite web |title=About The Tontine: History of The Tontine |publisher=The Cleveland Tontine |url=https://www.theclevelandtontine.com/about/ |accessdate=28 February 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Tontine pensions in the US: 1868\u20131906==\nTontines became associated with life insurance in the United States in 1868 when [[Henry Baldwin Hyde]] of the [[AXA Equitable Life Insurance Company|Equitable Life Assurance Society]] introduced them as a means of selling more life insurance and meeting the demands of competition. Over the next four decades, the Equitable and its imitators sold approximately 9 million policies \u2013 two-thirds of the nation's outstanding insurance contracts. During the [[Panic of 1873]] many life insurance companies went out of business as deteriorating financial conditions created solvency problems: those that survived had all offered tontines.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yang |first1=Tony |date=2009 |page=5 |title=The Performance of Life Insurance Companies: 1860\u20131905 |url=http://www.americasmutualbanks.com/images/0714_YangPaper.pdf }}</ref> However, the contracts included an obligation to maintain monthly payments, and as a result spawned large numbers of policy owners whose life savings were wiped out by a single missed payment. The profits produced by the tontines' deferred payout structures proved tempting for the issuers \u2013 especially the profligate [[James Hazen Hyde|James Hyde]]. As the funds in the investment account accumulated, they found their way into directors' and agents' pockets, and also into the hands of judges and legislators, who reciprocated with prejudicial judgments and laws.<ref>{{cite journal |first=William J. |last=Bernstein |title=King William's Tontine: Why the Retirement Annuity of the Future Should Resemble Its Past (a review) |journal=Financial Analysts Journal |publisher=CFA Institute |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=2015 |url=https://www.cfapubs.org/doi/full/10.2469/br.v10.n1.17 |accessdate=11 May 2018 |doi=10.2469/br.v10.n1.17 |doi-broken-date=2019-12-16 }}</ref> \n\nFinally, in 1905, the [[Armstrong Investigation]] was set up to enquire into the selling of tontines. It resulted in the banning of the continued sale of those tontines which contained toxic clauses for consumers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moss |first1=David |first2=Eugene |last2=Kintgen |title=The Armstrong Investigation |journal=Harvard Business School Case Collection |volume=708-034 |origyear=January 2008 |date=January 2009 |url=https://www.hbs.edu/faculty/Pages/item.aspx?num=35348 |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism from competitors==\nWhen Equitable Life Assurance was establishing its business in Australia in the 1880s, an actuary of the [[AMP Limited|Australian Mutual Provident Society]] criticised tontine insurance, calling it \"an immoral contract\" which \"put a premium on murder\".<ref>Buley 1967, p. 291.</ref> In New Zealand at the time, another of the chief critics of tontines had been the government, which also issued its own insurance.<ref>Buley 1967, p. 472.</ref>\n\n==Modern regulation==\nUntil recently, the First Life Directive of the European Union specified tontines as a class of insurance business however the new [[Pan-European Pension]] legislation coming into force in August 2020 specifically paves the way for non-insurance operators to create new pension products that abide by the \"tontine principle\".<ref name=\"meerten&hoog\"/>\n\nIn most places in the United States using tontines to raise capital or obtain lifetime income is consistently upheld as being legal; however, outdated legislation in two states has fostered the incorrect perception that selling tontines in the broader U.S. is illegal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tardi |first1=Carla |title=Tontine |url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/tontine.asp |website=Investopedia}}</ref>\n\n==Tontine pensions in the 21st Century==\nIn 2015, John Barry Forman and Michael J. Sabin, using modern actuarial techniques to calculate fair transfer payments when participants are of different ages and have made different contributions, proposed a new structure of [[pension]] plan on the tontine model, through which large employers could provide retirement income for their employees. They argued that tontine pensions would have two major advantages over traditional pensions, as they would always be fully funded, and the plan sponsor would not be required to bear the investment and actuarial risks.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.pennlawreview.com/print/163-U-Pa-L-Rev-755.pdf |first1=John Barry |last1=Forman |first2= Michael J. |last2=Sabin |title=Tontine Pensions |journal=[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]] |volume=163 |issue=3 |year=2015 |pages=755\u2013831 }}</ref> Similar arguments were put forward in the same year by [[Moshe Milevsky]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=King William's Tontine: Why the Retirement Annuity of the Future Should Resemble its Past|last=Milevsky|first=Moshe A.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1107076129|location=|pages=170\u201397}}</ref> In March 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that tontines were getting fresh consideration as a way for people to get steady retirement income.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Dean McClelland, Richard Fullmer and Jon Matonis and others published a whitepaper to deliver secure low cost Tontine Pensions based loosely upon the Forman, Sabin and Milevsky format under the brand [[Tontine Trust]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tontine.com/whitepaper-nt/TontineTrust.Non-Technical.Whitepaper.(V1.01D).pdf|title=Tontine Trust - Retirement Planning for the 21st Century|last=McClelland|first=Dean|date=November 15, 2017|website=Tontine.com}}</ref>  In 2018, Richard K. Fullmer and Michael J. Sabin expanded on the ideas presented in Forman and Sabin (2015) by showing that participants in an actuarially fair tontine need not be confined to a common investment portfolio or to a common payout method. Their paper introduced the concept of individual tontine accounts (ITAs), which they envisioned as complementary to individual retirement account (IRAs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=3217551|title=Individual Tontine Accounts|last=Fullmer|first=Richard K.|last2=Sabin|first2=Michael J.|date=July 21, 2018|website=SSRN}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[CFA Institute]] Research Foundation published a research brief titled ''Tontines: A Practitioner's Guide to Mortality-Pooled Investments'' noting that \"the study of fair tontine design is a specialty all its own\u2014one that has emerged only recently.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.cfainstitute.org/-/media/documents/article/rf-brief/fullmer-tontines-rf-brief.ashx|title=Tontines: A Practitioner's Guide to Mortality-Pooled Investments|last=Fullmer|first=Richard K.|publisher=CFA Institute Research Foundation|year=2019|isbn=978-1-944960-75-9|location=|pages=}}</ref> Fullmer and Sabin showed that it is possible to engineer payouts within a tontine structure that are immune to interest rate and reinvestment risk.<ref>Fullmer, Richard K. and Sabin, Michael J. (April 16, 2019). [https://ssrn.com/abstract=3373251 Tontine Bond Ladders]. Available at SSRN.</ref>\n\nSeveral new pension architectures have been designed or deployed which partially or fully utilise the tontine risk-sharing structure including:\n*Defined Ambition pensions\n*Target Benefit pensions\n*Collective Defined Contribution pensions or [[CDC Pensions]]\n\n==Variant uses of the term==\nIn French-speaking cultures, particularly in [[Developing country|developing countries]], the meaning of the term \"tontine\" has broadened to encompass a wider range of semi-formal group savings and [[microcredit]] schemes. The crucial difference between these and tontines in the traditional sense is that benefits do not depend on the deaths of other members.\n\nIn the UK during the mid-20th century, the term was applied to communal Christmas saving schemes, with participants making regular payments of an agreed sum through the year, which would be withdrawn shortly before Christmas to fund gifts and festivities.<ref>For a description and images of a contribution card, see {{cite web |title=Rhostyllen: a history through pictures |url=http://rhostyllen.info/misc.html |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAs a type of [[Rotating Savings and Credit Association|rotating savings and credit association]] (ROSCA), tontines are well established as a savings instrument in central Africa, and in this case function as savings clubs in which each member makes regular payments and is lent the [[wiktionary:kitty#noun|kitty]] in turn. They are wound up after each cycle of loans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ecole.org/seminaires/FS3/SEM105/VC190603-ENG.pdf |title=Using tontines to run the economy |first=Alain |last=Henry |publisher=l'\u00c9cole de Paris du management |date=June 19, 2003}}</ref> In West Africa, \"tontines\" \u2013 often consisting of mainly women \u2013 are an example of economic, social and cultural solidarity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dandc.eu/en/article/self-organised-savings-communities-tontines-are-example-economic-social-and-cultural |title=Flexible and disciplined |first=Eva-Maria |last=Bruchhaus |publisher=D+C, Development and Cooperation |date=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nInformal group savings and loan associations are also traditional in many east Asian societies, and under the name of tontines are found in [[Cambodia]], and among emigrant Cambodian communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cambodia.org.nz/Tontine.htm |title=Tontine: an alternative financial instrument in Cambodian communities |first=Man Hau |last=Liev |publisher=12th NZASIA Conference |date=November 26\u201329, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Singapore]], the Chit Funds Act of 1971<ref>{{cite web |title=Chit Funds Act |work=Singapore Statutes Online |origyear=1971 |year=2013 |url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Act/CFA1971 |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref> defines the application of legislation to the operation of [[chit fund]]s, which were also known colloquially as tontines but which operated on a different principle more commonly known as a ROSCA ([[Rotating Savings and Credit Association]]).\n \nIn [[Malaysia]], chit funds are primarily known as \"kootu funds\", which again are ROSCAs and which are defined under the ''Kootu Funds (Prohibition) Act 1971'' as \n\"...a scheme or arrangement variously known as a kootu, cheetu, chit fund, hwei, tontine or otherwise whereby the participants subscribe periodically or otherwise to a common fund and such common fund is put up for sale or payment to the participants by auction, tender, bid, ballot or otherwise...\" <ref>{{cite web |title=Kootu Funds (Prohibition) Act 1971 |work=Commonwealth Legal Information Institute |year=1971 |url=http://www.commonlii.org/my/legis/consol_act/kfa1971281/ |accessdate=27 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nTontines have been featured as plot devices in many fictional stories, movies and television programs, including:\n*''La Tontine'' (1708), a comic play by [[Alain-Ren\u00e9 Lesage]]. A physician, hoping to raise the funds to give his daughter a dowry, buys a tontine on the life of an elderly peasant, who he then strives to keep alive.\n*''The Great Tontine'' (1881), is a novel by [[Henry Hawley Smart|Hawley Smart]].\n*''[[The Wrong Box (novel)|The Wrong Box]]'' (1889), is a comic novel by [[Robert Louis Stevenson]] and [[Lloyd Osbourne]]. The plot revolves around a tontine originally taken out for some wealthy English children, and the resulting shenanigans as younger family members of the two final survivors vie to secure the final payout. The book was adapted as a [[The Wrong Box|film]], produced and directed by [[Bryan Forbes]], (1966).\n*''The Secret Tontine'' (1912), is an atmospheric faux-gothic novel by [[Robert Murray Gilchrist]], set in the [[Derbyshire]] [[Peak District]] during a snowy winter in the late 19th century. The plot involves the potential beneficiaries of a covert tontine, and their scheme to murder their ignorant rivals. \n*[[Lillian de la Torre]]'s short story \"The Tontine Curse\" (1948) features mysterious deaths related to a tontine in 1779, being investigated by [[Samuel Johnson]].\n*''The Tontine'' (1955), a novel by [[Thomas B. Costain]], illustrated by [[Herbert Ryman]], is set in nineteenth-century England and tells a story centered around the fictional \"Waterloo Tontine\", established to benefit veterans of the Napoleonic wars. Among other plot twists, shareholders hire an actor to impersonate a dead nominee, and conspire to murder another member.\n*In ''[[4.50 from Paddington]]'' (1957), a [[Miss Marple]] murder mystery by [[Agatha Christie]], the plot revolves around the will of a wealthy industrialist, which establishes a [[Settlement (trust)|settlement]] under which his estate is divided in trust among his grandchildren, the final survivor to inherit the whole. The settlement is described, inaccurately, as a tontine. \n*''[[Something Fishy]]'' (1957), a novel by [[P. G. Wodehouse]], features a so-called tontine under which the investors' sons stand to gain from marrying late.\n* In the U.S. television series ''[[The Wild Wild West]]'', Episode 16 of Season Two (1966\u201367) \u2013 \"The Night of the Tottering Tontine\" \u2013 finds James West and Artemus Gordon protecting a man who is a member of a tontine whose members are being murdered one by another.\n*\"Old Soldiers,\" an eighth-season episode of the television series ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', focuses on a tontine set up among Colonel Potter and several of his Army buddies from [[World War I]]. While taking shelter in a ch\u00e2teau during an artillery barrage, they had found a cache of brandy and drank all but one bottle, which they set aside for the last survivor. After the only other surviving member dies, Potter receives the bottle in the mail and shares it with his staff, drinking first to his departed friends and then to the new ones he has made at the 4077th.\n*In the ''[[Barney Miller]]'' episode \"The Tontine\" (1982), one of the last two surviving family members who invested in the tontine attempts to kill himself so that the other can have the money before growing too old to enjoy it.\n* In ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Raging Abe Simpson and His Grumbling Grandson in \"The Curse of the Flying Hellfish\"]]\" (1996), [[Grampa Simpson]] and [[Mr. Burns]] are the final survivors of a tontine to determine ownership of art looted during [[World War II]]. Grampa eventually kicks Burns out of the tontine for trying to kill him, but before he and Bart can do anything with the art, a descendant of the original owner shows up to claim it.\n*In [[S. L. Viehl]]'s science fiction multi-volume novel ''Stardoc'' (2000), the title character is accused of spreading a plague to several colony worlds, on one of which the colonists had established a tontine. The sole survivor, a little girl, consequently becomes so wealthy that in the second book of the series \u2013 ''Beyond Varallan'' (2000) \u2013 she buys the bank behind the colonies to free the Stardoc from the debt she now owes.\n*The 2001 comedy film ''[[Tomcats (2001 film)|Tomcats]]'' features a variation on a tontine where the last investor to get married gets the full amount of the invested funds.\n* In the ''[[Archer (2009 TV series)|Archer]]'' episode \"The Double Deuce\" (2011), Archer's [[valet]] Woodhouse is revealed as one of three final survivors of a group of World War I [[Royal Flying Corps]] squadron mates who each put [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]50 into an interest-bearing account, now worth nearly a million [[United States dollar|dollars]]. The office workers at ISIS HQ, realizing that a new tontine could capitalize on the high mortality rate of field agents, begin persuading people to join.\n* The ''[[Diagnosis: Murder]]'' episode \"Being of Sound Mind\" (Season 8 Episode 16) features a tontine as a motive for murder.\n*The ''[[The Brokenwood Mysteries|Brokenwood Mysteries]]'' episode \"Tontine\" (Season 5 Episode 3) centres on a tontine.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Buley|first=R. Carlyle|title=The Equitable Life Assurance Society of the United States 1859\u20131964|date=1967|publisher=Appleton-Century-Crofts|location=New York}}\n*{{cite book |first=Geoffrey |last=Clark |title=Betting on Lives: the culture of life insurance in England, 1695\u20131775 |location=Manchester |publisher=Manchester University Press |year=1999 |isbn=9780719056758 }} \n*{{Cite journal |first=Julien |last=Coudy |title=La Tontine royal sous le r\u00e8gne de Louis XIV |journal=Revue historique de droit fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9tranger |volume=4th ser. 35 |year=1957 |pages=128\u201333 |language=fr}}\n*{{Cite journal |first=John |last=Dunkley |title=Bourbons on the Rocks: tontines and early public lotteries in France |journal=Journal for Eighteenth-Century Studies |volume=30 |issue=3 |year=2007 |pages=309\u201323 |doi=10.1111/j.1754-0208.2007.tb00338.x}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Gallais Hamonno |first1=Georges |last2=Berthon |first2=Jean |title=Les emprunts tontiniers de l'Ancien R\u00e9gime: un exemple d'ing\u00e9nierie financi\u00e8re au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle |location=Paris |year=2008 |language=fr}}\n*{{cite journal|first=David R. |last=Green |title=Tontines, annuities and civic improvements in Georgian Britain |journal=Urban History |volume=46 |issue=4 |year=2019 |pages=649\u201394 |doi=10.1017/s0963926818000743 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Trout |first2=Andrew P. |title=The Tontine: fact and fiction |journal=Journal of European Economic History |volume=5 |year=1976 |pages=663\u201370 }}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Trout |first2=Andrew P. |title=The Tontine: from the reign of Louis XIV to the French Revolutionary era |location=Homewood, IL |year=1982 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last1=Jennings |first1=Robert M. |last2=Swanson |first2=Donald F. |last3=Trout |first3=Andrew P. |title=Alexander Hamilton's tontine proposal |journal=William and Mary Quarterly |series=3rd ser. |volume=45 |issue=1 |year=1988 |pages=107\u2013115 |jstor=1922216|doi=10.2307/1922216 }}\n*{{Cite journal |url=http://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1108&context=jcfl&sei-redir=1#search=%22fordham%20tontines%22 |first=Kent |last=McKeever |title=A Short History of Tontines |journal=[[Fordham Journal of Corporate & Financial Law]] |volume=15 |issue=2 |year=2011 |pages=491\u2013521}}\n*{{cite book |last=Milevsky |first=Moshe A. |authorlink=Moshe Milevsky |title=King William's Tontine: why the retirement annuity of the future should resemble its past |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |year=2015 |isbn=978-110-707612-9}}\n*{{Cite journal |first=David R. |last=Weir |title=Tontines, Public Finance, and Revolution in France and England, 1688\u20131789 |journal=Journal of Economic History |volume=49 |year=1989 |pages=95\u2013124 |doi=10.1017/s002205070000735x|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/6b6216730f9bb206697414ac38327061feb3673d }}\n*{{Cite book|author=Wyler, Julius |title=Die Tontinen in Frankreich |location=Munich and Leipzig |year=1916 |language=de}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|tontine}}\n*[[wikisource:The Story of Life Insurance/Chapter IV|\"The Great Tontine Gamble\"]], one of a series of articles by [[Burton J. Hendrick]] appearing in ''[[McClure's Magazine]]'' in 1906\n*[http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a3_172.html ''The Straight Dope'': \"What's with tontines, the odd annuities in which you benefit when others die?\"]\n*[http://www.cato.org/pubs/regulation/regv32n4/v32n4-4.pdf Baker et al. (Winter 2009-2010) \"Tontines for the Young Invincibles\", ''Regulation'']\n*[https://www.forbes.com/sites/pensionresearchcouncil/2018/01/30/fintechs-answer-to-the-global-retirement-crisis/#586b0cd31ff3 \"Forbes  Pensions Research Council (Jan 18, 2018) \"Fintech's Answer To The Global Retirement Crisis\"]\n\n{{Economic history of the Netherlands}}\n\n[[Category:Investment]]\n[[Category:Informal finance]]\n[[Category:1653 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:17th-century introductions]]\n[[Category:Economic history of the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Drinkllanito", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eModern regulation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tontine"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sint Eustatius", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Sint Eustatius}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sint Eustatius\n| map1 = File:St eustatius corono crop.gif\n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Sint Eustatius]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 31 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=31|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 2\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the [[Dutch Caribbean]] of [[Sint Eustatius]] on March 31, 2020. The island has a population of 3,139 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opendata.cbs.nl/statline/#/CBS/nl/dataset/83698NED/table?ts=1578654405815|title=Caribisch Nederland; bevolking; geslacht, leeftijd, burgerlijke staat|website=[[Centraal Bureau voor de Statistiek]]|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\nThe Queen Beatrix Medical Center run by the St. Eustatius Health Care Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sehcf.org/about/|title=About|website=St. Eustatius Health Care Foundation|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> provides the medical care on the island, but patients requiring intensive care need to be transported to [[Sint Maarten]].<ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\"/> Testing for Covid-19 is also being performed in Sint Maarten, but due to the limited capacity tests for people without symptoms are forwarded to [[Guadelope]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.saba-news.com/thursday-april-16-island-governor-jonathan-johnson-updates-on-covid-19-status/|title=Thursday, April 16: Island Governor Jonathan Johnson updates on Covid-19 status (audio message)|website=Saba News|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> which will take 3 to 5 days.<ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\">{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/02/sint-eustatius-aangeslagen-door-eerste-coronabesmettingen/ |title=Sint-Eustatius aangeslagen door eerste coronabesmettingen |language=nl|access-date=20 April 2020 |website=Caribisch Netwerk NTR }}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 16 March, the airport and harbor were closed to international travel from high risk area like [[Europe]] and the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://koninkrijk.nu/2020/03/16/tijdelijk-verbod-voor-de-burgerlijke-luchtvaart-in-caribisch-nederland-uitgebreid/ |title=Tijdelijk verbod voor de burgerlijke luchtvaart in Caribisch Nederland uitgebreid |access-date=20 April 2020|language=nl|website=Caribisch Netwerk NTR }}</ref>\n\nBy 26 March, there were no confirmed cases in the territory, with seven suspected cases coming back negative.<ref name=\"loop20200326\">{{Cite web|title=St Eustatius government tightens COVID-19 quarantine enforcement|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/st-eustatius-govt-tightens-covid-19-quarantine-enforcement-3|accessdate=2020-03-26|language=en|publisher=Loop|date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Schools have also been temporarily shut on the island.<ref name=\"loop20200326\"/> Most international visitors are also currently banned from entering the territory.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sint Eustatius implements travel restrictions due to COVID-19|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/sint-eustatius-implements-travel-restrictions-due-covid-19-4|accessdate=2020-03-27|language=en|publisher=Loop|date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, the first two cases were confirmed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus a yega Sint Eustatius: a confirma e prome 2 casonan! |url=https://24ora.com/coronavirus-a-yega-sint-eustatius-a-confirma-e-prome-2-casonan/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=24ora.com |date=31 March 2020 |language=Papiamento}}</ref> The patients are young men from the [[Netherlands]] who arrived on 15 March and self isolated soon after arrival. <ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\"/>\n\nOn 2 April, it was announced that restaurants, bars, sport centres had to close and that gatherings of over 25 people are banned.<ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\"/>\n\nOn 7 April, Peter Glerum has been appointed as crisis management advisor by the Public Entity of St. Eustatius.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bes-reporter.com/index.php/2020/04/16/statia-recruits-peter-glerum-as-crisis-management-advisor/|title=Statia recruits Peter Glerum as Crisis Management Advisor|website=BES reporter|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 19 April, 19 people have been tested and 15 people are in self quarantine. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/euxgov/?ref=py_c|title=Coronavirus update Sint-Eustatius|website=Government of Sint-Eustatius via Facebook|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saba]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Sint Eustatius]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Dutch Caribbean|Sint Eustatius]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Sint Eustatius]]\n\n{{#related:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Aruba}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saba}}\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{SintEustatius-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Sint Eustatius}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sint Eustatius\n| map1 = File:St eustatius corono crop.gif\n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Sint Eustatius]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 31 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=31|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 2\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the [[Dutch Caribbean]] of [[Sint Eustatius]] on March 31, 2020. The island has a population of 3,139 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opendata.cbs.nl/statline/#/CBS/nl/dataset/83698NED/table?ts=1578654405815|title=Caribisch Nederland; bevolking; geslacht, leeftijd, burgerlijke staat|website=[[Centraal Bureau voor de Statistiek]]|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\nThe Queen Beatrix Medical Center run by the St. Eustatius Health Care Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sehcf.org/about/|title=About|website=St. Eustatius Health Care Foundation|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> provides the medical care on the island, but patients requiring intensive care need to be transported to [[Sint Maarten]].<ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\"/> Testing for Covid-19 is also being performed in Sint Maarten, but due to the limited capacity tests for people without symptoms are forwarded to [[Guadelope]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.saba-news.com/thursday-april-16-island-governor-jonathan-johnson-updates-on-covid-19-status/|title=Thursday, April 16: Island Governor Jonathan Johnson updates on Covid-19 status (audio message)|website=Saba News|access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> which will take 3 to 5 days.<ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\">{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/02/sint-eustatius-aangeslagen-door-eerste-coronabesmettingen/ |title=Sint-Eustatius aangeslagen door eerste coronabesmettingen |language=nl|access-date=20 April 2020 |website=Caribisch Netwerk NTR }}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 16 March, the airport and harbor were closed to international travel from high risk area like [[Europe]] and the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://koninkrijk.nu/2020/03/16/tijdelijk-verbod-voor-de-burgerlijke-luchtvaart-in-caribisch-nederland-uitgebreid/ |title=Tijdelijk verbod voor de burgerlijke luchtvaart in Caribisch Nederland uitgebreid |access-date=20 April 2020|language=nl|website=Caribisch Netwerk NTR }}</ref>\n\nBy 26 March, there were no confirmed cases in the territory, with seven suspected cases coming back negative.<ref name=\"loop20200326\">{{Cite web|title=St Eustatius government tightens COVID-19 quarantine enforcement|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/st-eustatius-govt-tightens-covid-19-quarantine-enforcement-3|accessdate=2020-03-26|language=en|publisher=Loop|date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Schools have also been temporarily shut on the island.<ref name=\"loop20200326\"/> Most international visitors are also currently banned from entering the territory.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sint Eustatius implements travel restrictions due to COVID-19|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/sint-eustatius-implements-travel-restrictions-due-covid-19-4|accessdate=2020-03-27|language=en|publisher=Loop|date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, the first two cases were confirmed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus a yega Sint Eustatius: a confirma e prome 2 casonan! |url=https://24ora.com/coronavirus-a-yega-sint-eustatius-a-confirma-e-prome-2-casonan/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=24ora.com |date=31 March 2020 |language=Papiamento}}</ref> The two cases are young men from the [[Netherlands]] who arrived on 15 March and self isolated soon after arrival. <ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\"/>\n\nOn 2 April, it was announced that restaurants, bars, sport centres had to close and that gatherings of over 25 people are banned.<ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\"/>\n\nOn 7 April, Peter Glerum has been appointed as crisis management advisor by the Public Entity of St. Eustatius.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bes-reporter.com/index.php/2020/04/16/statia-recruits-peter-glerum-as-crisis-management-advisor/|title=Statia recruits Peter Glerum as Crisis Management Advisor|website=BES reporter|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 19 April, 19 people have been tested and 15 people are in self quarantine. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/euxgov/?ref=py_c|title=Coronavirus update Sint-Eustatius|website=Government of Sint-Eustatius via Facebook|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saba]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Sint Eustatius]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Dutch Caribbean|Sint Eustatius]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Sint Eustatius]]\n\n{{#related:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Aruba}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saba}}\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{SintEustatius-stub}}\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTimeline", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Sint_Eustatius"}
{"title_page": "Hope chest", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n[[File:Walnut hope chest (1570 - 1600, in Northern Italy). Nymph. - Budapest Museum of Applied Arts.JPG|thumb|Intricate designs; typically the most decorated in the home during the prime time of the hope chest.]]\nA '''hope chest''', also called '''dowry chest''', '''cedar chest''', '''trousseau chest''' or '''glory box''' is a piece of furniture traditionally used to collect items such as clothing and household linen, by unmarried young women in anticipation of married life.\n\nThe term \"hope chest\" or \"cedar chest\" is used in the midwest or south of the United States; in the United Kingdom, the term is \"bottom drawer\"; while both terms, and \"glory box\" are used by women in Australia.<ref>https://www.macquariedictionary.com.au/features/word/search/?word=glory+box&search_word_type=Dictionary</ref><ref name=Kingston>{{cite book|last=Kingston|first=Beverley|title=My Wife, My Daughter and Poor Mary Ann - Women and Work in Australia|year=1977|publisher=Nelson|location=Melbourne|isbn=0-17-005212-5|pages=102}} \"By the turn of the [20th] century the trousseau and the glory-box had become accepted institutions for the readers of the weekly and monthly women's magazines.\"</ref> \n[[File:Friis Nybo Girl Inspecting Her Hope Chest.jpg|thumb|Girl inspecting her hope chest, by Poul Friis Nybo, c. 1900]]\n[[File:Arca de la Batalla de Anghiari (M.A.N. 51936) 01.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]] hope chest (''[[cassone]]'') from [[Republic of Florence|Florence]] (15th century)]]\n\n== Social context ==\nUsing her own needlework skills to construct a [[dowry|trousseau]] and stock her glory-box \"was for the working girl the equivalent of planning and saving for marriage on the part of the provident and ambitious young man.\"<ref name=Kingston /> \nThe collection of a ''trousseau'' was a common coming-of-age rite until approximately the 1950s; it was typically a step on the road to marriage between courting a man and engagement. It wasn't always collected in a special chest, hence the alternative UK term ''bottom drawer'', which refers to putting aside one drawer in a [[chest of drawers]] for collecting the trousseau undisturbed, but such a chest was an acceptable gift for a girl approaching a marriageable age.\n\nContents of a \"hope chest\" or \"glory box\" included typical [[dowry]] items such as clothing (especially a special dress), table linens, towels, bed linens, quilts and occasionally dishware.  As a bride would typically leave home on marriage, hope chests were sometimes made with an eye to portability, albeit infrequently. Examples of hand-made items made between 1916 and 1918 for a trousseau by a prospective bride are on display in the [[National Museum of Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cotton nightdress made by Muriel McPhee|url=http://www.nma.gov.au/exhibitions/australian_journeys/gallery_highlights?result_6095_result_page=4|publisher=National Museum of Australia|accessdate=2012-02-22}}</ref>  In this case, the trousseau\u2014never used because its creator's fianc\u00e9 was killed in [[World War I]] before the marriage took place\u2014was stored in [[Calico (textile)|calico]] bags rather than in a chest.\n\nThe hope chest was often used for the firstborn girl of a family. Instead of just having sheets and household linen in the bottom drawer, this box would transport these goods and dowries and then later be used as a standard piece of furniture for the lady of the house to use. This dowry chest was often richly decorated, however over time dowry chests gradually became smaller, with jewelry boxes emerging instead of large dowry boxes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aramcoworld.com/en-US/Articles/November-2015/The-Art-of-the-Dowry-Chest|title=The Art of the Dowry Chest|last=Stone|first=Caroline|date=2015|website=[[Saudi Aramco World]]|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref>\n\nBy contrast, a \"bridal chest\" was given to a bride at her wedding, by her husband, and so is not a \"hope chest\" in this sense.\n\n== Historical origins ==\n[[File:Italian - \"Cassone\" - Walters 6535.jpg|thumb|Italian - \"Cassone\" - Walters 6535]]\n* Cassone of [[renaissance Italy]]\n[[File:Aussteuerschrank fcm.jpg|thumb|''Aussteuerschrank'' - a dowry closet, currently in a German museum.]]\n: Large decorated and showy chests, forming part of dynastic marriages in 15th and 16th century Italy. These were prized displays of wealth, of even more value than their contents.\n\n* Dutch [[kast (furniture)|kast]] or German [[Schrank (furniture)|Schrank]]\n: These are tall wardrobe-like chests with double doors. These are larger than most hope chests, intended for regular service in the home after marriage, and so were constructed as to partially dismantle for transport.<ref name=\"Schleining, Treasure Chests\" >{{cite book\n  |title=Treasure Chests: The Legacy of Extraordinary Boxes\n  |last= Schleining |first= Lon \n  |isbn=1-56158-651-X\n  |publisher=[[Taunton Press]]\n  |year=2003\n  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kOHS2418gQYC\n}}</ref>\n\n* American settlers\n: The peak of the hope chest as folk art came with the waves of [[History of immigration to the United States#Immigration 1850 to 1930|European immigrants to America]]. Many of these, from Scandinavia to the Northern Midwest and Germans in Pennsylvania ([[Amish]], had long traditions of plainly constructed chests with extensive painted decoration.\n\n* Arabic origins\n: These chests were also known as \"dower chests\" in the Middle East. \"The more than 300,000 surviving documents in the Cairo [[Genizah]] are one of our richest sources of insight into daily life in [[Egypt]] from the ninth to the 19th centuries. Among them are numerous marriage contracts, and almost all refer to a dower chest. For it, we see two names used: The muqaddimah<ref>The \"muqaddimah\" means \"first\", and possibly refers to the fact that it was carried by the lead donkey in the traditional bridal procession to the groom's home.</ref> was specifically for the bride\u2019s personal possessions; sunduq, which normally came in matching pairs, were for other goods. They were not usually elaborately decorated, except in the case of the ruling class.\"<ref>[http://www.aramcoworld.com/en-US/Articles/November-2015/The-Art-of-the-Dowry-Chest \"The Art of the Dowery Chest.\"] by Caroline Stone. Aramco World. Volume 66, (8). November\u2013December 2015. [ISSN]: 1530-5821. Page 27.</ref>\n\n== Suffocation hazard to children ==\n\nThere have been several instances of child deaths due to suffocation inside hope chests, due to the piece's traditional design which can trap children under a heavy and sometimes self-locking lid.<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=Boy dies in hope chest \n  |author=Lauren Sellers\n  |date=7 February 2008\n  |publisher=Orlando Sentinel\n  |url=http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/Archive/Alt/alt.true-crime/2008-02/msg00544.html}}</ref>  \n<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=Two Franklin children who were trapped inside of hope chest have died, Norfolk DA says \n  |author=Peter Schworm and John R. Ellement\n  |date=13 January 2014\n  |publisher=Boston Globe\n  |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/2014/01/13/two-franklin-children-who-were-trapped-inside-hope-chest-have-died-norfolk-says/kxLmxTOZHhrbH8lyN7Tq3N/story.html}}</ref> In 1996, following reports of at least six child suffocation deaths, the manufacturer Lane Furniture recalled 12 million hope chests, the lids of which latched shut automatically, and could not be opened from the inside. Specifically, the recall applied to the locks of all \"Lane\" and \"Virginia Maid\" cedar chests manufactured between 1912 and 1987. As part of the recall, they provide new lock latch configuration replacement parts. However, they estimated that 6 million chests still used the recalled lock latch. As of 2020, Lane Furniture still offered replacement locks through their website.<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=Product Safety Advisory \u2013 Lane Cedar Chests\n  |publisher=Lane Home Furnishings\n  |url=https://www.lanefurniture.com/page/product-safety}}</ref>\n\n== Styles ==\nThe typical hope chest is of lidded [[blanket chest]] form. In some traditions, there may also be one or two side-by-side drawers beneath. As with blanket chests, a small [[till (furniture)|till]] may also be found inside for small items.\n\n=== Lane Company chests ===\nAs the contents of such a chest would primarily be linens, construction in moth-repellent [[cedrus|cedar]], or at least a cedar lining, was popular. The [[Altavista, Virginia#Lane Home Furnishings|Lane Company]] of [[Altavista, Virginia]] (active 1912-2001)<ref name=\"Lane\" >{{cite web\n  |title=History Corner: Lane Cedar Chests\n  |url=http://www.vahistorical.org/publications/historycorner_lane.htm\n  |publisher=Virginia Historical Society\n}}</ref> were a notable maker of cedar chests. After developing production-line techniques for making ammunition boxes during World War I, they turned these production techniques (and a patented locking-mitre corner joint) into vast numbers of chests. This was aided by strong advertising, using a teenaged [[Shirley Temple]] as a model, in a campaign targeted at [[G.I. (military)|GI]]s and absentee sweethearts of [[World War II]]. They were particularly well known for their practice (since 1930) of distributing miniature (9\" long) cedar chests to girls graduating from high-school as advertising gifts.<ref name=\"Schleining, Treasure Chests\" />  The Eastern Redcedar (''[[Juniperus virginiana]]'') is the \"cedar\" used in making moth-repelling cedar chests and drawers, as well as pencils.\n\n=== Decoration ===\nDecoration is not an intrinsic part of the hope chest, but often appears.\n* Carving\n: Carving was notable in the 17th and 18th century joined oak chests. The Hadley chests of [[Hadley, Massachusetts|Massachusetts]] are covered by extensive surface carving in the typical low-relief style of the period.\n* Painting\n: This is typically seen in the Scandinavian and German immigrant traditions and follows traditional styles. In many Arab countries, they are still referred to as \"sanduq \u2018arus\", or \u201cwedding box,\u201d although modern trends have them made of metal rather than wood, and looking more like a footlocker. They are elaborately painted, often with a mosque dome or architectural design on the lid, with the color red predominating.<ref>[http://www.aramcoworld.com/en-US/Articles/November-2015/The-Art-of-the-Dowry-Chest \"The Art of the Dowery Chest.\"] by Caroline Stone. Aramco World. Volume 66, (8). November\u2013December 2015. [ISSN]: 1530-5821. Page 29.</ref>\n* [[Gesso]]\n: The elaborate gilded gesso of the [[cassone|cassoni]] was produced by skilled and expensive craftsmen. This work has not been seen since and doesn't form part of the folk tradition.\n* [[Sulfur inlay]]\n: Sulfur inlay is a rare technique in furniture and for chests it is only known for a short period. Between 1765 and around 1820, [[Pennsylvania Dutch|German immigrant]] cabinetmakers in [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]] used it to decorate the surface of chests. The Deitrich chest of 1783 is now in the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]].<ref name=\"Schleining, Treasure Chests\" />\n\n== In popular culture ==\nIn the 1920s, 'hope chest' was [[slang]] for a [[pack of cigarettes]].<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=59 More Slang Phrases From The 1920s We Should Start Using Again \n  |author=Nico Lang\n  |date=6 October 2013\n  |publisher=Thought Catalog\n  |url=http://thoughtcatalog.com/nico-lang/2013/10/59-more-slang-phrases-from-the-1920s-we-should-start-using-again/\n}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Glory Box (Portishead song)|Glory Box]]\" is also the title of a song from the band [[Portishead (band)|Portishead]]. The song is about a woman who is giving up her time as a temptress to commit to a settled life with a man, asking him to take a look from her side every now and then.\n\nIn the 1985 movie ''[[Back to the Future]]'',<ref name=\"Back to the Future\">{{cite video\n  |people=Michael J. Fox (Star)\n  |date=1985\n  |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0088763/\n  |title=Back to the Future\n  |medium=Motion picture\n  |location=\n}}</ref> the character Lorraine McFly refers to having placed Marty McFly's pants \"over there...on my hope chest\" after he had been knocked unconscious. The joke implies her romantic interest in Marty when, unbeknownst to Lorraine, Marty is her son from the future.\n\nIn ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', [[Kurt Hummel]] has claimed to own a hope chest. This is an ironic inversion of the hope chest's usual role for a prospective bride, as Kurt is a gay teenage boy.\n\nIn the 2012 film ''[[The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey]]'', [[Bilbo Baggins]] asks [[K\u00edli|Kili]] to \"please not do that\" on his mother's glory box, when the [[dwarf (Middle-earth)|dwarf]] cleans his boots on the chest. This suggests that in [[Middle Earth]] women (possibly from the high society) also used hope chests, at least in [[Hobbiton]].\n\nIn ''[[Me and You and Everyone We Know]]'', Peter and Robbies' neighbor has a hope chest, which is a part of the climax of the film.\n\nIn ''[[The New Yankee Workshop]]'', [[Norm Abram]] demonstrates how to build and paint a [[Pennsylvania Dutch]]-style hope chest (called a dower chest in the episode) modeled on one on display at the [[Winterthur Museum, Garden and Library|Winterthur Museum]] in [[Delaware]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dower]]\n*[[Bride price]]\n*[[Dowry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|hope chests}}\n{{Wiktionary|glory box}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hope Chest}}\n[[Category:Chests (furniture)]]\n[[Category:Marriage]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n[[File:Walnut hope chest (1570 - 1600, in Northern Italy). Nymph. - Budapest Museum of Applied Arts.JPG|thumb|Intricate designs; typically the most decorated in the home during the prime time of the hope chest.]]\nA '''hope chest''', also called '''dowry chest''', '''cedar chest''', '''trousseau chest''' or '''glory box''' is a piece of furniture traditionally used to collect items such as clothing and household linen, by unmarried young women in anticipation of married life.\n\nThe term \"hope chest\" or \"cedar chest\" is used in the midwest or south of the United States; in the United Kingdom, the term is \"bottom drawer\"; while both terms, and \"glory box\" are used by women in Australia.<ref>https://www.macquariedictionary.com.au/features/word/search/?word=glory+box&search_word_type=Dictionary</ref><ref name=Kingston>{{cite book|last=Kingston|first=Beverley|title=My Wife, My Daughter and Poor Mary Ann - Women and Work in Australia|year=1977|publisher=Nelson|location=Melbourne|isbn=0-17-005212-5|pages=102}} \"By the turn of the [20th] century the trousseau and the glory-box had become accepted institutions for the readers of the weekly and monthly women's magazines.\"</ref> \n[[File:Friis Nybo Girl Inspecting Her Hope Chest.jpg|thumb|Girl inspecting her hope chest, by Poul Friis Nybo, c. 1900]]\n[[File:Arca de la Batalla de Anghiari (M.A.N. 51936) 01.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]] hope chest (''[[cassone]]'') from [[Republic of Florence|Florence]] (15th century)]]\n\n== Social context ==\nUsing her own needlework skills to construct a [[dowry|trousseau]] and stock her glory-box \"was for the working girl the equivalent of planning and saving for marriage on the part of the provident and ambitious young man.\"<ref name=Kingston /> \nThe collection of a ''trousseau'' was a common coming-of-age rite until approximately the 1950s; it was typically a step on the road to marriage between courting a man and engagement. It wasn't always collected in a special chest, hence the alternative UK term ''bottom drawer'', which refers to putting aside one drawer in a [[chest of drawers]] for collecting the trousseau undisturbed, but such a chest was an acceptable gift for a girl approaching a marriageable age.\n\nContents of a \"hope chest\" or \"glory box\" included typical [[dowry]] items such as clothing (especially a special dress), table linens, towels, bed linens, quilts and occasionally dishware.  As a bride would typically leave home on marriage, hope chests were sometimes made with an eye to portability, albeit infrequently. Examples of hand-made items made between 1916 and 1918 for a trousseau by a prospective bride are on display in the [[National Museum of Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cotton nightdress made by Muriel McPhee|url=http://www.nma.gov.au/exhibitions/australian_journeys/gallery_highlights?result_6095_result_page=4|publisher=National Museum of Australia|accessdate=2012-02-22}}</ref>  In this case, the trousseau\u2014never used because its creator's fianc\u00e9 was killed in [[World War I]] before the marriage took place\u2014was stored in [[Calico (textile)|calico]] bags rather than in a chest.\n\nThe hope chest was often used for the firstborn girl of a family. Instead of just having sheets and household linen in the bottom drawer, this box would transport these goods and dowries and then later be used as a standard piece of furniture for the lady of the house to use. This dowry chest was often richly decorated, however over time dowry chests gradually became smaller, with jewelry boxes emerging instead of large dowry boxes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aramcoworld.com/en-US/Articles/November-2015/The-Art-of-the-Dowry-Chest|title=The Art of the Dowry Chest|last=Stone|first=Caroline|date=2015|website=[[Saudi Aramco World]]|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref>\n\nBy contrast, a \"bridal chest\" was given to a bride at her wedding, by her husband, and so is not a \"hope chest\" in this sense.\n\n== Historical origins ==\n[[File:Italian - \"Cassone\" - Walters 6535.jpg|thumb|Italian - \"Cassone\" - Walters 6535]]\n* Cassone of [[renaissance Italy]]\n[[File:Aussteuerschrank fcm.jpg|thumb|''Aussteuerschrank'' - a dowry closet, currently in a German museum.]]\n: Large decorated and showy chests, forming part of dynastic marriages in 15th and 16th century Italy. These were prized displays of wealth, of even more value than their contents.\n\n* Dutch [[kast (furniture)|kast]] or German [[Schrank (furniture)|Schrank]]\n: These are tall wardrobe-like chests with double doors. These are larger than most hope chests, intended for regular service in the home after marriage, and so were constructed as to partially dismantle for transport.<ref name=\"Schleining, Treasure Chests\" >{{cite book\n  |title=Treasure Chests: The Legacy of Extraordinary Boxes\n  |last= Schleining |first= Lon \n  |isbn=1-56158-651-X\n  |publisher=[[Taunton Press]]\n  |year=2003\n  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kOHS2418gQYC\n}}</ref>\n\n* American settlers\n: The peak of the hope chest as folk art came with the waves of [[History of immigration to the United States#Immigration 1850 to 1930|European immigrants to America]]. Many of these, from Scandinavia to the Northern Midwest and Germans in Pennsylvania ([[Amish]], had long traditions of plainly constructed chests with extensive painted decoration.\n\n* Arabic origins\n: These chests were also known as \"dower chests\" in the Middle East. \"The more than 300,000 surviving documents in the Cairo [[Genizah]] are one of our richest sources of insight into daily life in [[Egypt]] from the ninth to the 19th centuries. Among them are numerous marriage contracts, and almost all refer to a dower chest. For it, we see two names used: The muqaddimah<ref>The \"muqaddimah\" means \"first\", and possibly refers to the fact that it was carried by the lead donkey in the traditional bridal procession to the groom's home.</ref> was specifically for the bride\u2019s personal possessions; sunduq, which normally came in matching pairs, were for other goods. They were not usually elaborately decorated, except in the case of the ruling class.\"<ref>[http://www.aramcoworld.com/en-US/Articles/November-2015/The-Art-of-the-Dowry-Chest \"The Art of the Dowery Chest.\"] by Caroline Stone. Aramco World. Volume 66, (8). November\u2013December 2015. [ISSN]: 1530-5821. Page 27.</ref>\n\n== Suffocation hazard to children ==\n\nThere have been several instances of child deaths due to suffocation inside hope chests, due to the piece's traditional design which can trap children under a heavy and sometimes self-locking lid.<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=Boy dies in hope chest \n  |author=Lauren Sellers\n  |date=7 February 2008\n  |publisher=Orlando Sentinel\n  |url=http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/Archive/Alt/alt.true-crime/2008-02/msg00544.html}}</ref>  \n<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=Two Franklin children who were trapped inside of hope chest have died, Norfolk DA says \n  |author=Peter Schworm and John R. Ellement\n  |date=13 January 2014\n  |publisher=Boston Globe\n  |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/2014/01/13/two-franklin-children-who-were-trapped-inside-hope-chest-have-died-norfolk-says/kxLmxTOZHhrbH8lyN7Tq3N/story.html}}</ref> In 1996, following reports of at least six child suffocation deaths, the manufacturer Lane Furniture recalled 12 million hope chests, the lids of which latched shut automatically, and could not be opened from the inside. Specifically, the recall applied to the locks of all \"Lane\" and \"Virginia Maid\" cedar chests manufactured between 1912 and 1987. As part of the recall, they provide new lock latch configuration replacement parts. However, they estimated that 6 million chests still used the recalled lock latch. As of 2020, Lane Furniture still offered replacement locks through their website.ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=Product Safety Advisory \u2013 Lane Cedar Chests\n  |publisher=Lane Home Furnishings\n  |url=https://www.lanefurniture.com/page/product-safety}}</ref>\n\n== Styles ==\nThe typical hope chest is of lidded [[blanket chest]] form. In some traditions, there may also be one or two side-by-side drawers beneath. As with blanket chests, a small [[till (furniture)|till]] may also be found inside for small items.\n\n=== Lane Company chests ===\nAs the contents of such a chest would primarily be linens, construction in moth-repellent [[cedrus|cedar]], or at least a cedar lining, was popular. The [[Altavista, Virginia#Lane Home Furnishings|Lane Company]] of [[Altavista, Virginia]] (active 1912-2001)<ref name=\"Lane\" >{{cite web\n  |title=History Corner: Lane Cedar Chests\n  |url=http://www.vahistorical.org/publications/historycorner_lane.htm\n  |publisher=Virginia Historical Society\n}}</ref> were a notable maker of cedar chests. After developing production-line techniques for making ammunition boxes during World War I, they turned these production techniques (and a patented locking-mitre corner joint) into vast numbers of chests. This was aided by strong advertising, using a teenaged [[Shirley Temple]] as a model, in a campaign targeted at [[G.I. (military)|GI]]s and absentee sweethearts of [[World War II]]. They were particularly well known for their practice (since 1930) of distributing miniature (9\" long) cedar chests to girls graduating from high-school as advertising gifts.<ref name=\"Schleining, Treasure Chests\" />  The Eastern Redcedar (''[[Juniperus virginiana]]'') is the \"cedar\" used in making moth-repelling cedar chests and drawers, as well as pencils.\n\n=== Decoration ===\nDecoration is not an intrinsic part of the hope chest, but often appears.\n* Carving\n: Carving was notable in the 17th and 18th century joined oak chests. The Hadley chests of [[Hadley, Massachusetts|Massachusetts]] are covered by extensive surface carving in the typical low-relief style of the period.\n* Painting\n: This is typically seen in the Scandinavian and German immigrant traditions and follows traditional styles. In many Arab countries, they are still referred to as \"sanduq \u2018arus\", or \u201cwedding box,\u201d although modern trends have them made of metal rather than wood, and looking more like a footlocker. They are elaborately painted, often with a mosque dome or architectural design on the lid, with the color red predominating.<ref>[http://www.aramcoworld.com/en-US/Articles/November-2015/The-Art-of-the-Dowry-Chest \"The Art of the Dowery Chest.\"] by Caroline Stone. Aramco World. Volume 66, (8). November\u2013December 2015. [ISSN]: 1530-5821. Page 29.</ref>\n* [[Gesso]]\n: The elaborate gilded gesso of the [[cassone|cassoni]] was produced by skilled and expensive craftsmen. This work has not been seen since and doesn't form part of the folk tradition.\n* [[Sulfur inlay]]\n: Sulfur inlay is a rare technique in furniture and for chests it is only known for a short period. Between 1765 and around 1820, [[Pennsylvania Dutch|German immigrant]] cabinetmakers in [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]] used it to decorate the surface of chests. The Deitrich chest of 1783 is now in the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]].<ref name=\"Schleining, Treasure Chests\" />\n\n== In popular culture ==\nIn the 1920s, 'hope chest' was [[slang]] for a [[pack of cigarettes]].<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=59 More Slang Phrases From The 1920s We Should Start Using Again \n  |author=Nico Lang\n  |date=6 October 2013\n  |publisher=Thought Catalog\n  |url=http://thoughtcatalog.com/nico-lang/2013/10/59-more-slang-phrases-from-the-1920s-we-should-start-using-again/\n}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Glory Box (Portishead song)|Glory Box]]\" is also the title of a song from the band [[Portishead (band)|Portishead]]. The song is about a woman who is giving up her time as a temptress to commit to a settled life with a man, asking him to take a look from her side every now and then.\n\nIn the 1985 movie ''[[Back to the Future]]'',<ref name=\"Back to the Future\">{{cite video\n  |people=Michael J. Fox (Star)\n  |date=1985\n  |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0088763/\n  |title=Back to the Future\n  |medium=Motion picture\n  |location=\n}}</ref> the character Lorraine McFly refers to having placed Marty McFly's pants \"over there...on my hope chest\" after he had been knocked unconscious. The joke implies her romantic interest in Marty when, unbeknownst to Lorraine, Marty is her son from the future.\n\nIn ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', [[Kurt Hummel]] has claimed to own a hope chest. This is an ironic inversion of the hope chest's usual role for a prospective bride, as Kurt is a gay teenage boy.\n\nIn the 2012 film ''[[The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey]]'', [[Bilbo Baggins]] asks [[K\u00edli|Kili]] to \"please not do that\" on his mother's glory box, when the [[dwarf (Middle-earth)|dwarf]] cleans his boots on the chest. This suggests that in [[Middle Earth]] women (possibly from the high society) also used hope chests, at least in [[Hobbiton]].\n\nIn ''[[Me and You and Everyone We Know]]'', Peter and Robbies' neighbor has a hope chest, which is a part of the climax of the film.\n\nIn ''[[The New Yankee Workshop]]'', [[Norm Abram]] demonstrates how to build and paint a [[Pennsylvania Dutch]]-style hope chest (called a dower chest in the episode) modeled on one on display at the [[Winterthur Museum, Garden and Library|Winterthur Museum]] in [[Delaware]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dower]]\n*[[Bride price]]\n*[[Dowry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|hope chests}}\n{{Wiktionary|glory box}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hope Chest}}\n[[Category:Chests (furniture)]]\n[[Category:Marriage]]\n", "name_user": "Natbadge", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSuffocation hazard to children:Fixed missing bracket", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hope_chest"}
{"title_page": "Substrate integrated waveguide", "text_new": "A '''Substrate integrated waveguide (SIW)''' (also known as '''post-wall waveguide''' or '''laminated waveguide''') is a synthetic [[Waveguide (radio frequency)|rectangular electromagnetic waveguide]] formed in a [[dielectric]] substrate by densely arraying metallized posts or [[Via (electronics)|via-hole]]s which connect the upper and lower metal plates of the substrate. The waveguide can be easily fabricated with low-cost mass-production using [[Through-hole technology|through-hole techniques]] where the post walls consists of [[via fence]]s. SIW is known to have similar guided wave and mode characteristics to conventional rectangular waveguide with equivalent [[guide wavelength]].\n\nSince the emergence of new communication technologies in the 1990s, there has been an increasing need for high-performance millimeter-wave systems. These need to be reliable, low-cost, compact, and compatible with high-frequencies. Unfortunately, above 10&nbsp;GHz, the well known [[microstrip]] and [[coplanar waveguide|coplanar lines]] technologies cannot be used because they have high insertion and radiation losses at these frequencies. The [[Waveguide (radio frequency)|rectangular waveguide]] topology can overcome these issues as it offers an excellent immunity against radiation losses and presents low insertion losses. But in their classical form, rectangular waveguide is not compatible with the miniaturization required by modern applications.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ke Wu|last2=Desiandes|first2=D.|last3=Cassivi|first3=Y.|date=2003|title=The substrate integrated circuits - a new concept for high-frequency electronics and optoelectronics|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1246173/|journal=6th International Conference on Telecommunications in Modern Satellite, Cable and Broadcasting Service, 2003. TELSIKS 2003.|location=Serbia, Montenegro, Nis|publisher=IEEE|volume=1|pages=P\u2013III\u2013P-X|doi=10.1109/TELSKS.2003.1246173|isbn=978-0-7803-7963-3}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of SIW was developed in the early 2000s by [[Ke Wu]] to reconcile those requirements.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Deslandes|first=D.|last2=Ke Wu|date=2001|title=Integrated transition of coplanar to rectangular waveguides|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/966971/|journal=2001 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Sympsoium Digest (Cat. No.01CH37157)|location=Phoenix, AZ, USA|publisher=IEEE|volume=2|pages=619\u2013622|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2001.966971|isbn=978-0-7803-6538-4}}</ref> The authors presented a platform for integrating all the components of a microwave circuit inside a single substrate, with a rectangular cross-section. Using a single substrate guarantees a limited volume and a simplicity of manufacture, while the rectangular cross-section of the line provides the advantages of the waveguide topology in terms of losses.[[File:SIW sanstransparence.svg|thumb|Three-dimensional configuration of a classical substrate integrated waveguide. The propagating electromagnetic waves are confined inside the substrate because of the two metallic layers on the two faces of the substrate and the two rows of metallic vias connecting them.]]\n\n== Principles of SIW ==\n\n[[File:SIW horizontal.png|alt=Horizontal cross-section of a classical substrate integrated waveguide.|thumb|Horizontal cross-section of a classical substrate integrated waveguide. The propagating electromagnetic waves are confined inside the substrate because of the two metallic layers on the two faces of the substrate and the two rows of metallic vias connecting them. The center-to-center distance of two successive vias is <math>s</math>, their diameter is <math>d</math> and the center-to-center distance between the two rows of vias is <math>a</math>. The effective width <math>a_e</math>, computed from <math>a</math>, <math>d</math> and <math>s</math>,with is also presented.]]\n\n=== Geometry ===\n\nA classical SIW is composed of a thin dielectric substrate covered on both faces by a metallic layer. The substrate embeds two parallel rows of metallic [[via (electronics)|via-holes]] delimiting the wave propagation area. The organization of the vias and the geometric parameters are described in the attached figure.\n\nThe width of a SIW is the distance <math>a</math> between its two vias rows, which is defined from center-to-center. An [[#Effective width|effective width]] <math>a_e</math> may be used to characterize more precisely the wave propagation. The distance between two successive vias of the same row is <math>s</math>, and the vias diameter is denoted by <math>d</math>.\n\n=== Transverse magnetic propagation modes ===\n\nIn classical rectangular waveguide, the general formulation of propagation involves a superposition of [[Transverse mode|transverse electric]] (TE) and [[Transverse mode|transverse magnetic]] (TM) modes. Each of these is associated with particular fields and currents. In the case of TM modes, the current in the vertical walls is longitudinal, i.e. parallel to the propagation axis, usually denoted as <math>z</math>. Then, given the vertical geometry of the vias, it is impossible for such modes to appear in SIW's: the electrical current cannot propagate from via to via. Only TE modes are able to propagate through SIW.\n\nEach mode appears above a precise cut-off frequency determined by the waveguide dimensions and the filling medium. For TM modes, decreasing the waveguide thickness (usually denoted as <math>b</math>) increases the cut-off frequency with <math>1/b</math>. In the case of SIW, the thickness is so low that the cut-off frequency of TM modes is much higher than the dominant mode.\n\n=== Effective width ===\n\nOne of the objectives of the SIW geometry is to reproduce the characteristic propagation modes of rectangular waveguides inside a thin template. The width <math>a</math> of the waveguide is an essential parameter of those modes. In the typical SIW geometry, <math>a</math> is the distance between the two vias rows from center-to-center (see figure). Due to the vias geometry, this distance cannot be utilized directly; because of the space between successive vias and their circular shape, the signal inside the guide does not behave exactly as it would in a perfectly rectangular waveguide of the same width.\n\nTo apply waveguide theory to SIWs, an effective width <math>a_\\text{eff}</math>can be used. Its takes into account the shape of the vias and the space in-between. Its value lies between <math>a + d</math> and <math>a - d</math>.\n\nA common simple definition is<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=M.|last2=Georgiadis|first2=A.|last3=Wu|first3=K.|date=2011|title=Review of substrate-integrated waveguide circuits and antennas|url=https://digital-library.theiet.org/content/journals/10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463|journal=IET Microwaves, Antennas & Propagation|language=en|volume=5|issue=8|pages=909|doi=10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Cassivi|first=Y.|last2=Perregrini|first2=L.|last3=Arcioni|first3=P.|last4=Bressan|first4=M.|last5=Wu|first5=K.|last6=Conciauro|first6=G.|date=September 2002|title=Dispersion characteristics of substrate integrated rectangular waveguide|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1031925/|journal=IEEE Microwave and Wireless Components Letters|volume=12|issue=9|pages=333\u2013335|doi=10.1109/LMWC.2002.803188|issn=1531-1309}}</ref>\n\n<math>a_\\text{eff} = a - \\frac{d^2}{0.95 s}</math>\n\nand a more refined definition used for large values of <math>d/a</math> is,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Feng Xu|last2=Ke Wu|date=January 2005|title=Guided-wave and leakage characteristics of substrate integrated waveguide|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1381676/|journal=IEEE Transactions on Microwave Theory and Techniques|volume=53|issue=1|pages=66\u201373|doi=10.1109/TMTT.2004.839303|issn=0018-9480}}</ref><br /><math>a_\\text{eff} = a - 1.08 \\frac{d^2}{s} + 0.1 \\frac{d^2}{a}.</math>\n\nUsing this effective width, the propagation constant of a SIW will be similar to that of a classical rectangular waveguide whose width is <math>a_\\text{eff}</math>. The formulas given above are empirical: they were established comparing the dispersion characteristics of different SIWs to those of rectangular waveguide filled with the same dielectric material.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n* {{section link|Planar transmission line|Substrate integrated waveguide}}, also\n** {{section link|Planar transmission line|Transitions}}\n** {{section link|Planar transmission line|Circuit gallery}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.microwaves101.com/encyclopedias/substrate-integrated-waveguide Substrate Integrated Waveguide], at microwave101.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Substrate_Integrated_Waveguide}}\n[[Category:Planar transmission lines]]\n[[Category:Electronic design]]\n[[Category:Microwave technology]]\n[[Category:Electronics manufacturing]]\n", "text_old": "A '''Substrate integrated waveguide (SIW)''' (also known as '''post-wall waveguide''' or '''laminated waveguide''') is a synthetic [[Waveguide (radio frequency)|rectangular electromagnetic waveguide]] formed in a [[dielectric]] substrate by densely arraying metallized posts or [[Via (electronics)|via-hole]]s which connect the upper and lower metal plates of the substrate. The waveguide can be easily fabricated with low-cost mass-production using [[Through-hole technology|through-hole techniques]] where the post walls consists of [[via fence]]s. SEW is known to have similar guided wave and mode characteristics to conventional rectangular waveguide with equivalent [[guide wavelength]].\n\nSince the emergence of new communication technologies in the 1990s, there has been an increasing need for high-performance millimeter-wave systems. These need to be reliable, low-cost, compact, and compatible with high-frequencies. Unfortunately, above 10&nbsp;GHz, the well known [[microstrip]] and [[coplanar waveguide|coplanar lines]] technologies cannot be used because they have high insertion and radiation losses at these frequencies. The [[Waveguide (radio frequency)|rectangular waveguide]] topology can overcome these issues as it offers an excellent immunity against radiation losses and presents low insertion losses. But in their classical form, rectangular waveguide is not compatible with the miniaturization required by modern applications.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ke Wu|last2=Desiandes|first2=D.|last3=Cassivi|first3=Y.|date=2003|title=The substrate integrated circuits - a new concept for high-frequency electronics and optoelectronics|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1246173/|journal=6th International Conference on Telecommunications in Modern Satellite, Cable and Broadcasting Service, 2003. TELSIKS 2003.|location=Serbia, Montenegro, Nis|publisher=IEEE|volume=1|pages=P\u2013III\u2013P-X|doi=10.1109/TELSKS.2003.1246173|isbn=978-0-7803-7963-3}}</ref>\n\nThe concept of SIW was developed in the early 2000s by [[Ke Wu]] to reconcile those requirements.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Deslandes|first=D.|last2=Ke Wu|date=2001|title=Integrated transition of coplanar to rectangular waveguides|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/966971/|journal=2001 IEEE MTT-S International Microwave Sympsoium Digest (Cat. No.01CH37157)|location=Phoenix, AZ, USA|publisher=IEEE|volume=2|pages=619\u2013622|doi=10.1109/MWSYM.2001.966971|isbn=978-0-7803-6538-4}}</ref> The authors presented a platform for integrating all the components of a microwave circuit inside a single substrate, with a rectangular cross-section. Using a single substrate guarantees a limited volume and a simplicity of manufacture, while the rectangular cross-section of the line provides the advantages of the waveguide topology in terms of losses.[[File:SIW sanstransparence.svg|thumb|Three-dimensional configuration of a classical substrate integrated waveguide. The propagating electromagnetic waves are confined inside the substrate because of the two metallic layers on the two faces of the substrate and the two rows of metallic vias connecting them.]]\n\n== Principles of SIW ==\n\n[[File:SIW horizontal.png|alt=Horizontal cross-section of a classical substrate integrated waveguide.|thumb|Horizontal cross-section of a classical substrate integrated waveguide. The propagating electromagnetic waves are confined inside the substrate because of the two metallic layers on the two faces of the substrate and the two rows of metallic vias connecting them. The center-to-center distance of two successive vias is <math>s</math>, their diameter is <math>d</math> and the center-to-center distance between the two rows of vias is <math>a</math>. The effective width <math>a_e</math>, computed from <math>a</math>, <math>d</math> and <math>s</math>,with is also presented.]]\n\n=== Geometry ===\n\nA classical SIW is composed of a thin dielectric substrate covered on both faces by a metallic layer. The substrate embeds two parallel rows of metallic [[via (electronics)|via-holes]] delimiting the wave propagation area. The organization of the vias and the geometric parameters are described in the attached figure.\n\nThe width of a SIW is the distance <math>a</math> between its two vias rows, which is defined from center-to-center. An [[#Effective width|effective width]] <math>a_e</math> may be used to characterize more precisely the wave propagation. The distance between two successive vias of the same row is <math>s</math>, and the vias diameter is denoted by <math>d</math>.\n\n=== Transverse magnetic propagation modes ===\n\nIn classical rectangular waveguide, the general formulation of propagation involves a superposition of [[Transverse mode|transverse electric]] (TE) and [[Transverse mode|transverse magnetic]] (TM) modes. Each of these is associated with particular fields and currents. In the case of TM modes, the current in the vertical walls is longitudinal, i.e. parallel to the propagation axis, usually denoted as <math>z</math>. Then, given the vertical geometry of the vias, it is impossible for such modes to appear in SIW's: the electrical current cannot propagate from via to via. Only TE modes are able to propagate through SIW.\n\nEach mode appears above a precise cut-off frequency determined by the waveguide dimensions and the filling medium. For TM modes, decreasing the waveguide thickness (usually denoted as <math>b</math>) increases the cut-off frequency with <math>1/b</math>. In the case of SIW, the thickness is so low that the cut-off frequency of TM modes is much higher than the dominant mode.\n\n=== Effective width ===\n\nOne of the objectives of the SIW geometry is to reproduce the characteristic propagation modes of rectangular waveguides inside a thin template. The width <math>a</math> of the waveguide is an essential parameter of those modes. In the typical SIW geometry, <math>a</math> is the distance between the two vias rows from center-to-center (see figure). Due to the vias geometry, this distance cannot be utilized directly; because of the space between successive vias and their circular shape, the signal inside the guide does not behave exactly as it would in a perfectly rectangular waveguide of the same width.\n\nTo apply waveguide theory to SIWs, an effective width <math>a_\\text{eff}</math>can be used. Its takes into account the shape of the vias and the space in-between. Its value lies between <math>a + d</math> and <math>a - d</math>.\n\nA common simple definition is<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bozzi|first=M.|last2=Georgiadis|first2=A.|last3=Wu|first3=K.|date=2011|title=Review of substrate-integrated waveguide circuits and antennas|url=https://digital-library.theiet.org/content/journals/10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463|journal=IET Microwaves, Antennas & Propagation|language=en|volume=5|issue=8|pages=909|doi=10.1049/iet-map.2010.0463}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Cassivi|first=Y.|last2=Perregrini|first2=L.|last3=Arcioni|first3=P.|last4=Bressan|first4=M.|last5=Wu|first5=K.|last6=Conciauro|first6=G.|date=September 2002|title=Dispersion characteristics of substrate integrated rectangular waveguide|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1031925/|journal=IEEE Microwave and Wireless Components Letters|volume=12|issue=9|pages=333\u2013335|doi=10.1109/LMWC.2002.803188|issn=1531-1309}}</ref>\n\n<math>a_\\text{eff} = a - \\frac{d^2}{0.95 s}</math>\n\nand a more refined definition used for large values of <math>d/a</math> is,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Feng Xu|last2=Ke Wu|date=January 2005|title=Guided-wave and leakage characteristics of substrate integrated waveguide|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1381676/|journal=IEEE Transactions on Microwave Theory and Techniques|volume=53|issue=1|pages=66\u201373|doi=10.1109/TMTT.2004.839303|issn=0018-9480}}</ref><br /><math>a_\\text{eff} = a - 1.08 \\frac{d^2}{s} + 0.1 \\frac{d^2}{a}.</math>\n\nUsing this effective width, the propagation constant of a SIW will be similar to that of a classical rectangular waveguide whose width is <math>a_\\text{eff}</math>. The formulas given above are empirical: they were established comparing the dispersion characteristics of different SIWs to those of rectangular waveguide filled with the same dielectric material.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n* {{section link|Planar transmission line|Substrate integrated waveguide}}, also\n** {{section link|Planar transmission line|Transitions}}\n** {{section link|Planar transmission line|Circuit gallery}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.microwaves101.com/encyclopedias/substrate-integrated-waveguide Substrate Integrated Waveguide], at microwave101.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Substrate_Integrated_Waveguide}}\n[[Category:Planar transmission lines]]\n[[Category:Electronic design]]\n[[Category:Microwave technology]]\n[[Category:Electronics manufacturing]]\n", "name_user": "VK Vivien", "label": "safe", "comment": "SEW to SIW", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Substrate_integrated_waveguide"}
{"title_page": "Charles S. Mott Prize", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Nevill Mott Medal and Prize}}\nThe '''Charles S. Mott Prize''' was awarded annually by the General Motors Cancer Research Foundation as one of a trio of scientific prizes entirely devoted to cancer research, the other two being the Charles F. [[Kettering Prize]] and the [[Alfred P. Sloan, Jr. Prize]]. The prizes, worth US$250,000, were awarded annually between 1979 and 2005. The awards were generally considered the most prestigious in the field.<ref name=\"Cancer Research 1999 pp. 1673s\u20131673s\">{{cite journal | title=Laureates: General Motors Cancer Research Awards | journal=Cancer Research | volume=59 | issue=7 Supplement | date=1 March 1999 | issn=0008-5472 | pages=1673s | url=http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/59/7_Supplement/1673s | access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.gm.com/company/gmability/philanthropy/cancer_research/prize.htm \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313231403/http://www.gm.com/company/gmability/philanthropy/cancer_research/prize.htm \n |title=GM Cancer Previous Prize Winners \n |publisher=General Motors \n |archivedate=13 March 2007 \n |accessdate=12 August 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\nThe Mott Prize was awarded for \"the most outstanding recent contribution related to the cause or prevention of cancer\". In 2006, due to financial pressures on the corporation supporting the Foundation, the three awards were consolidated into a single $250,000 General Motors Cancer Research Award.{{who|date=August 2012}}{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}. In 2006, the first and only winner of the General Motors Cancer Research Award was [[Napoleone Ferrara]].<ref>{{cite journal | year = 2006| title = Napoleone Ferrara wins 2006 GM Cancer Research Award | url = https://www.landesbioscience.com/journals/cbt/article/3155/ | journal = Cancer Biology & Therapy | volume = 5 | issue = 7| pages = 708\u2013709 | doi = 10.4161/cbt.5.7.3155 | pmid = 17022136 }}</ref>\n\nSince 2006 no further prizes have been awarded.\n\n==Laureates==\n{|\n|\n*2005 {{ill|Gerald Wogan|de}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070327215718/http://olw.mit.edu/profile.olw?3]\n*2004 [[Charles J. Sherr]] [http://www.hhmi.org:80/research/investigators/sherr.html]\n*2003 [[Yuan Chang]], [[Patrick S. Moore]]\n*2002 [[Richard Peto]]\n*2001 {{ill|Frank E. Speizer|de}}, [[Walter Willett]]\n*2000 [[Bert Vogelstein]]\n*1999 [[Arnold J. Levine]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20070701202734/http://bcrfcure.org/rese_meet_levine.html]\n*1998 [[Suzanne Cory]], [[Stanley J. Korsmeyer]]\n*1997 [[M. Judah Folkman]]\n*1996 [[Paul L. Modrich]], [[Richard Kolodner]]\n*1995 [[Frederick Pei Li]], [[Joseph F. Fraumeni]]\n*1994 [[Anthony R. Hunter|Tony Hunter]]\n*1993 [[Carlo M. Croce|Carlo Croce]] [http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v434/n7035/full/nj7035-938c.html]\n*1992 [[Brian MacMahon]]\n*1991 [[Peter K. Vogt]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20080524033235/http://www.scripps.edu/news/endeavor/endeavor1.1/vogt.html]\n*1990 [[Webster K. Cavenee]], [[Raymond L. White]] [https://archive.is/20070801131405/http://www.galloresearch.org/site/WhiteLab/section.php?id=192]\n*1989 [[Peter Nowell|Peter C. Nowell]], [[Janet D. Rowley]]\n*1988 [[Alfred G. Knudson]]\n*1987 [[R. Palmer Beasley]], {{ill|Jesse Summers|de}}\n*1986 [[Harald zur Hausen]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20081209135007/http://www.cancerworld.org/CancerWorld/getStaticModFile.aspx?id=717]\n*1985 {{ill|J. Christopher Wagner|de}}\n*1984 [[Robert C. Gallo]]\n*1983 [[Bruce Ames]]\n*1982 [[Denis P. Burkitt]]\n*1981 [[Takashi Sugimura]]\n*1980 {{ill|James A. Miller (biochemist)|de|3=James A. Miller|lt=James A. Miller}}, [[Elizabeth C. Miller]] [http://www.bookrags.com/biography/elizabeth-c-miller-and-james-a-miller-woc/]\n*1979 [[Richard Doll]]\n|\n<gallery perrow=\"4\" class=\"float-right\">\n Bert Vogelstein giving the Trent Lecture.jpg|2000: Bert Vogelstein\n Paul L. Modrich 0151.jpg|1996: Paul L.