{"title_page": "Caliphate (TV series)", "text_new": "'''''Caliphate''''' (Swedish: ''Kalifat'') is a 2020 Swedish thriller drama TV series. It premiered on January 12, 2020 on [[Sveriges Television]]. It became the most-viewed series ever on [[SVT Play]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/endemol-shine-caliphate-breaks-all-time-records-svt-play-1234574452/ |title=Endemol Shine\u2019s \u2018Caliphate\u2019 Breaks All-Time Records on SVT Play |date=April 8, 2020 |first=John |last=Hopewell |newspaper=Variety}}</ref>\n\nThe story is based on Fatima, an agent of the [[Swedish Security Service]], who receives a tip that a terror attack is being planned in Sweden.\n\nAll eight episodes were directed by [[Goran Kapetanovi\u0107]].\n\n\"Caliphate\" was made available globally on [[Netflix]] on March 18.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe story starts with Pervin, a young woman from Sweden who lives in Raqqa, Syria, with her husband Husam. They have a young daughter. Disillusioned with life in Raqqa, Pervin is looking to return to Sweden. After acquiring a cell phone from her neighbor and friend, she contacts Dolores, an antiradicalization advocate, in Sweden. Dolores puts Pervin in touch with Fatima, who is an agent of Swedish Security Service. Fatima is at odds with the leadership due to some previous incident with \"Lorentz\". Fatima starts talking with Pervin over the phone and tries to work her for intelligence related to a terror attack being planned in Sweden in exchange for safe return for Pervin and her daughter to Sweden.\n\nPervin tells Fatima about \"Al Musafir\" or the Traveler, who is in Sweden and is planning the attack. Al Musafir is Ibrahim \"Ibbe\" Haddad who is working as a teachers assistant in a Muslim highschool, while recruiting others like Jacob, Emil and Miryam into the terror attack. He simultaneously tries to radicalize young girls at the high school by sharing recruitment videos and propaganda. He successfully recruits Sulle and her friend Kerima, both 15yr old girls who start wearing the hijab and taking lessons in following the righteous path. The girls are shown pictures of palaces and told that if they moved to the Caliphate, they could live in luxury and be part of something special. Sulle's parents wisen up to their daughters radicalization and try to stop her unsuccessfully. Sulle inadvertently pulls her 13 yr old sister Lisha into the ideology, the implications of which are not fully realized until later in the show.\n\nFatima does not reveal her source (Pervin) to her superiors, but does reveal vague details about a terror plot. Her superiors tell her to drop the investigation and have her suspended for consuming cannabis. She remains in touch with her lover in the Security Service, Calle and continues to share information with him. She continues extracting information from Pervin and tries to piece together details of the plot. She gets on Jacob and Emils trail when she happens to be at an abandoned shooting range that she hears of from Pervin. Jacob gets her license plate and tracks it down.\n\nDolores and Ibbe are at an anti-radicalization meeting, when Ibbe steps out to talk with Jacob. The host shows an ISIS video and points to a tattoo on the forearm of one of the terrorists. Later while at a cafe, Dolores sees the tattoo on Ibbe's arm. After Ibbe drops her off, she calls Fatima who asks her to meet her at her apartment. When she goes there, she gets stabbed and dies. When Fatima arives, an alert has been issued to bring her in and she plans to escape. She goes to Dolores's house to get some cash and supplies, but two Swedish cops end up there. She locks them in a bathroom under gun point, which triggers a manhunt for her. She finds shelter at the home of her dad's colleague.\n\nPervin becomes the focus of attention for one of Husams colleagues (Ahmed), who arrives one night to her house and catches her talking to Fatima. He rapes her and is about to kill her when she stabs him. She throws his body into her neighbors well. Husam is under the influence of sleeping medicines and happens to walk into the kitchen and see the blood on the floor, but Pervin convinces him that he is dreaming. He never quite forgets and becomes convinced that he killed Ahmed, until Pervin finally tells him the truth.\n\nFatima seeks helps to extricate Pervin and a plan is set to remove her from Raqqa. Meanwhile, Sulle and Kerima have tickets to travel to Turkey and are picked up by Ibbe and the woman who has been teaching them about Islam. At the last minute, Sulle's younger sister Lisha joins them in the car and they set off for the airport. Sulle lied to her parents about going to a basketball game. Her dad finishes work early and decides to go and watch her game but sees that the stadium is empty. He calls Calle who sets off an alert with authorities in Germany and Turkey. They believe they have tracked the girls on their way to Istanbul only to realize that the passports had been switched and that the girls were in fact in Ankara. They decide to intercept the transport vehicle at the border between Turkey and Syria. They manage to rescue everyone except for Lisha who is en route to Syria.\n\nCalle convinces Fatima to seek help from Pervin to save Lisha. Pervin and her daughter have reached their transport vehicle when Fatima convinces her to return home and save Lisha. In return Fatima would personnaly come to Syria to rescue them all. Pervin convinces Husam to take Lisha on as his second wife. \n\nFatima is trailing Jacob and Emil but loses their trail after they switch cars at their mothers house. Fatima learns of the three terror targets minutes before the police close in on her location and she is taken into custody before she can share any information. In return for the information she promises to extricate Husam along with Pervin and Lisha. All three terror attacks are stopped anyway by the Security Service, who knew about them all along. They kept Fatima in the dark because they did not trust her. In exchange for her silence, she is released from jail. Ibbe escapes narrowly.\n\nFatima travels to Syria to rescue Pervin, Lisha, and Husam. Minutes before she arrives, Husam's colleague arrives to take Husam for a suicide bombing. Husam tries to buy time but Lisha, who is completely radicalized and unwilling to return to Sweden, reveals their escape plan. Husam's colleague shoots Pervin and is about to shoot Husam when Fatima shoots him. They quickly move to the car but Lisha does not join, so they leave her behind. They make it outside Raqqa but Fatima dies just after the border post. Husam carries his daughter and they make it back to Sweden. \n\nSulle and Kerima are being interrogated by the Security Service. Sulle gives up Ibbe's identity in an effort to save her sister Lisha. Kerima tries to commit suicide and is taken to a mental health facility where she gets her hands on a cell phone and warms Ibbe that his cover may be blown. Calle is at the school to bring Ibbe into custody, but Ibbe escapes. Kerima meets up with Ibbe and decides to participate in a new attack on a girls concert. Kerima is to wear a suicide vest that she cannot remove once she puts it on. Ibbe convinces Kerima that Sulle and he were also part of the attack and would be wearing similar suicide vests. Kerima texts Sulle after putting on the suicide vest only to learn that Ibbe had lied. She warns all the attendees who flee and waits for the bomb to explode. Ibbe triggers the bomb.\n\n==Cast==\n\n* [[Gizem Erdogan]] \u2013 Pervin El Kaddouri\n* [[Aliette Opheim]] \u2013 Fatima Zukic\n* [[Nora Rios]] \u2013 Suleika \"Sulle\" Wasem\n* [[Amed Bozan]] \u2013 Husam El Kaddouri\n* [[Yussra El Abdouni]] \u2013 Lisha Wasem\n* [[Arvin Kananian]] \u2013 Nadir Al-Shahrani\n* [[Lancelot Ncube]] \u2013 Ibrahim \"Ibbe\" Haddad\n* [[William Legue]] \u2013 Omar Soudani\n* [[Simon Mezher]] \u2013 Suleiman Wasem\n* [[Amanda Sohrabi]] \u2013 Kerima\n* [[Albin Grenholm]] \u2013 Calle\n* [[Marcus V\u00f6geli]] \u2013 Jakob Johannisson\n* [[Nils Wetterholm]] \u2013 Emil Johannisson\n\n* [[Ala Riani]] \u2013 Tuba Wasem\n* [[Dennis \u00d6nder]] \u2013 Abu Jibril\n* [[Shada Helin-Sulhav]] \u2013 Miryam\n* [[Marcel Khouri]] \u2013 Ahmed Mohamedi\n* [[Monica Albornoz]] \u2013 Dolores\n* [[Camilla Larsson]] \u2013 Sara\n* [[Jonatan Qahoush]] \u2013 Khalaf\n* [[Caisa Ankarsparre]] \u2013 Nyhetsankare\n* [[Ali Jalal]] \u2013 Ali Chatik\n* [[Ahmad Srour]] \u2013 Emiren\n* [[Maria Alm Norell]] \u2013 Anna-Karin\n* [[Nadeem Srouji]] \u2013 Karwan\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Netflix title|80240005}}\n*{{IMDb title|11398870}}\n\n[[Category:2020 television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Swedish drama television series]]\n[[Category:Sveriges Television programmes]]\n", "text_old": "'''''Caliphate''''' (Swedish: ''Kalifat'') is a 2020 Swedish thriller drama TV series. It premiered on January 12, 2020 on [[Sveriges Television]]. It became the most-viewed series ever on [[SVT Play]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/endemol-shine-caliphate-breaks-all-time-records-svt-play-1234574452/ |title=Endemol Shine\u2019s \u2018Caliphate\u2019 Breaks All-Time Records on SVT Play |date=April 8, 2020 |first=John |last=Hopewell |newspaper=Variety}}</ref>\n\nThe story is based on Fatima, an agent of the [[Swedish Security Service]], who receives a tip that a terror attack is being planned in Sweden.\n\nAll eight episodes were directed by [[Goran Kapetanovi\u0107]].\n\n\"Caliphate\" was made available globally on [[Netflix]] on March 18.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe story starts with Pervin, a young woman from Sweden who lives in Raqqa, Syria, with her husband Husam. They have a young daughter. Disillusioned with life in Raqqa, Pervin is looking to return to Sweden. After acquiring a cell phone from her neighbor and friend, she contacts Dolores, an antiradicalization advocate, in Sweden. Dolores puts Pervin in touch with Fatima, who is an agent of Swedish Security Service. Fatima is at odds with the leadership due to some previous incident with \"Lorentz\". Fatima starts talking with Pervin over the phone and tries to work her for intelligence related to a terror attack being planned in Sweden in exchange for safe return for Pervin and her daughter to Sweden.\n\nPervin tells Fatima about \"Al Musafir\" or the Traveler, who is in Sweden and is planning the attack. Al Musafir is Ibrahim \"Ibbe\" Haddad who is working as a teachers assistant in a Muslim highschool, while recruiting others like Jacob, Emil and Miryam into the terror attack. He simultaneously tries to radicalize young girls at the high school by sharing recruitment videos and propaganda. He successfully recruits Sulle and her friend Kerima, both 15yr old girls who start wearing the hijab and taking lessons in following the righteous path. The girls are shown pictures of palaces and told that if they moved to the Caliphate, they could live in luxury and be part of something special. Sulle's parents wisen up to their daughters radicalization and try to stop her unsuccessfully. Sulle inadvertently pulls her 13 yr old sister Lisha into the ideology, the implications of which are not fully realized until later the show.\n\nFatima does not reveal her source (Pervin) to her superiors, but does reveal vague details about a terror plot. Her superiors tell her to drop the investigation and have her suspended for consuming cannabis. She remains in touch with her lover in the Secret Service, Calle and continues to share information with him. She continues extracting information from Pervin and tries to piece together details of the plot. She gets on Jacob and Emils trail when she happens to be at an abandoned shooting range that she hears of from Pervin. Jacob gets her license plate and tracks it down.\n\nDolores and Ibbe are at an anti-radicalization meeting, when Ibbe steps out to talk with Jacob. The host shows an ISIS video and points to a tattoo on the forearm of one of the terrorists. Later while at a cafe, Dolores sees the tattoo on Ibbe's arm. After Ibbe drops her off, she calls Fatima who asks her to meet her at her apartment. When she goes there, she gets stabbed and dies. When Fatima arives, an alert has been issued to bring her in and she plans to escape. She goes to Dolores's house to get some cash and supplies, but two Swedish cops end up there. She locks them in a bathroom under gun point, which triggers a manhunt for her. She finds shelter at the home of her dad's colleague and continue working Pervin for details about the terror attack.\n\nPervin becomes the focus of attention for one of Husams colleagues (Ahmed), who arrives one night to her house and catches her talking to Fatima. He rapes her and is about to kill her when she stabs him. She throws his body into her neighbors well after being coached by Fatima. Husam is under the influence of sleeping medicines and happens to walk into the kitchen and see the blood on the floor, but Pervin convinces him that he is dreaming. He never quite forgets and becomes convinced that he killed Ahmed, until Pervin finally tells him the truth.\n\nFatima seeks helps to extricate Pervin and a plan is set to remove her from Raqqa. Meanwhile, Sulle and Kerima have tickets to travel to Turkey and are picked up by Ibbe and the woman who has been teaching them about Islam. At the last minute, Sulle's younger sister Lisha joins them in the car and they set off for the airport. Sulle lied to her parents about going to a basketball game. Her dad finishes work early and decides to go and watch her game but sees that the stadium is empty. He calls Calle who sets off an alert with authorities in Germany and Turkey. They believe they have tracked the girls on their way to Istanbul only to realize that the passports had been switched and that the girls were in fact in Ankara. They decide to intercept the transport vehicle at the border between Turkey and Syria. They manage to rescue everyone except for Lisha who is en route to Syria.\n\nCalle convinces Fatima to seek help from Pervin to save Lisha. Pervin and her daughter have reached their transport vehicle when Fatima convinces her to return home and save Lisha. In return Fatima would personnaly come to Syria to rescue them all. Pervin convinces Husam to take Lisha on as his second wife. \n\nFatima is trailing Jacob and Emil but loses their trail after they switch cars at their mothers house. Fatima learns of the three terror targets minutes before the police close in on her location and she is taken into custody before she can share any information. In return for the information she promises to extricate Husam along with Pervin and Lisha. All three terror attacks are stopped anyway by the Security Service, who knew about them all along. They kept Fatima in the dark because they did not trust her. In exchange for her silence, she is released from jail. Ibbe escapes narrowly.\n\nFatima travels to Syria to rescue Pervin and her daughter, Lisha, and Husam. Minutes before she arrives, Husam's colleague arrives to take Husam for a suicide bombing. Husam tries to buy time but Lisha, who is completely radicalized and unwilling to return to Sweden, reveals their escape plan. Husam's colleague shoots Pervin and is about to shoot Husam when Fatima shoots him. They quickly move to the car but Lisha does not join, so they leave her behind. They make it outside Raqqa but Fatima dies just after the border post. \n\nSulle and Kerima are being interrogated by the Security Service. Sulle gives up Ibbe's identity in an effort to save her sister Lisha. Kerima tries to commit suicide and is taken to a mental health facility where she gets her hands on a cell phone and warms Ibbe that his cover may be blown. Calle is at the school to bring Ibbe into custody, but he escapes having received a warning from Kerima. Kerima meets up with Ibbe and decides to participate in a new attack on a girls concert. Kerima is to wear a suicide vest that she cannot remove once she puts it on. Ibbe convinces Kerima that Sulle and he were also part of the attack and would be wearing similar suicide vests. Kerima texts Sulle after putting on the suicide vest only to learn that Ibbe had lied. She warns all the attendees who flee and waits for the bomb to explode. Ibbe triggers the bomb.\n\n==Cast==\n\n* [[Gizem Erdogan]] \u2013 Pervin El Kaddouri\n* [[Aliette Opheim]] \u2013 Fatima Zukic\n* [[Nora Rios]] \u2013 Suleika \"Sulle\" Wasem\n* [[Amed Bozan]] \u2013 Husam El Kaddouri\n* [[Yussra El Abdouni]] \u2013 Lisha Wasem\n* [[Arvin Kananian]] \u2013 Nadir Al-Shahrani\n* [[Lancelot Ncube]] \u2013 Ibrahim \"Ibbe\" Haddad\n* [[William Legue]] \u2013 Omar Soudani\n* [[Simon Mezher]] \u2013 Suleiman Wasem\n* [[Amanda Sohrabi]] \u2013 Kerima\n* [[Albin Grenholm]] \u2013 Calle\n* [[Marcus V\u00f6geli]] \u2013 Jakob Johannisson\n* [[Nils Wetterholm]] \u2013 Emil Johannisson\n\n* [[Ala Riani]] \u2013 Tuba Wasem\n* [[Dennis \u00d6nder]] \u2013 Abu Jibril\n* [[Shada Helin-Sulhav]] \u2013 Miryam\n* [[Marcel Khouri]] \u2013 Ahmed Mohamedi\n* [[Monica Albornoz]] \u2013 Dolores\n* [[Camilla Larsson]] \u2013 Sara\n* [[Jonatan Qahoush]] \u2013 Khalaf\n* [[Caisa Ankarsparre]] \u2013 Nyhetsankare\n* [[Ali Jalal]] \u2013 Ali Chatik\n* [[Ahmad Srour]] \u2013 Emiren\n* [[Maria Alm Norell]] \u2013 Anna-Karin\n* [[Nadeem Srouji]] \u2013 Karwan\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Netflix title|80240005}}\n*{{IMDb title|11398870}}\n\n[[Category:2020 television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Swedish drama television series]]\n[[Category:Sveriges Television programmes]]\n", "name_user": "Darnibee", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caliphate_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "The Damned (1947 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1947 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Les Maudits (English: The Damned)\n| image          = The Damned (1947 film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]\n| producer       = [[Andr\u00e9 Paulv\u00e9]]\n| writer         = [[Victor Alexandrov]]<br>[[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]<br>[[Jacques Compan\u00e9ez]]<br>[[Henri Jeanson]]<br>[[Jacques R\u00e9my (writer)|Jacques R\u00e9my]]\n| starring       = [[Henri Vidal]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Henri Alekan\n| editing        = Roger Dwyre\n| distributor    = [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont]]\n| released       = {{film date|1947|09|19|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''The Damned''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Les Maudits'''}}) is a 1947 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]].<ref>{{cite web|work=[[PopMatters]]|title=The Young Baron of 'The Damned' Was Seen Coming Out of One of Those Clubs|first=J.C.|last=Ma\u00e7ek III|date=26 August 2013|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/174623-the-damned/}}</ref> It was entered into the [[1947 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/4234/year/1947.html |title=Festival de Cannes: The Damned |accessdate=5 January 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> The film is notable for its depiction of the interior of a wartime submarine and for its tracking shots through the length of the U-boat.\n\n==Plot==\nAs Germany is in the throes of losing World War II, a number of wealthy Nazis and some French sympathizers head for South America in a German submarine leaving from Oslo. The film's narrator is a French doctor ([[Henri Vidal]]) who has been kidnapped to tend a sick woman, Hilde Garosi ([[Florence Marly]]), the wife of one man and the lover of another, both aboard. The doctor realizes he will be murdered at any point once the woman has recovered so he tries various stratagems to escape. All fail.\n\nThe mission slowly disintegrates as the war ends and its reasons for being dissipate, with some passengers either trying to escape or committing suicide. Forster ([[Jo Dest]]) tries to continue the mission even after Berlin has fallen and orders have gone out for all U-boats to surrender at the nearest port. Part of the crew finally mutinies against the insane ones still fighting the war. The doctor ends up alone on the Nazi sub for days writing his memoirs until an American ship rescues him and finally sinks his infamous abode at sea.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Marcel Dalio]] as Larga (as Dalio)\n* [[Henri Vidal]] as Docteur Guilbert\n* [[Florence Marly]] as Hilde Garosi\n* [[Fosco Giachetti]] as Garosi\n* [[Paul Bernard (actor)|Paul Bernard]] as Couturier\n* [[Jo Dest]] as Forster (as Jodest)\n* [[Michel Auclair]] as Willy Morus\n* {{ill|Anne Campion|fr}} as Ingrid Ericksen\n* [[Andreas von Halberstadt]] (as A. Von Halberstadt)\n* [[Lucien Hector]] as Ericksen\n* [[Jean Lozach]] (as Lozach)\n* [[Karl M\u00fcnch]] (as Karl Munch)\n\n==Restoration==\nIn 2013, the [[Cohen Film Collection]] released ''The Damned'' on Blu-ray and DVD in the US,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Damned|url=http://cohenmedia.net/the-damned|work=Cohenmedia.net}}</ref> using a restoration carried out by the French distributor, [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0039615}}\n\n{{Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment |state=collapsed}}\n{{Palme d'Or 1939-1959}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Damned, The}}\n[[Category:1947 films]]\n[[Category:1947 drama films]]\n[[Category:French black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]\n[[Category:World War II submarine films]]\n[[Category:Palme d'Or winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1947 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Les Maudits (English: The Damned)\n| image          = The Damned (1947 film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]\n| producer       = [[Andr\u00e9 Paulv\u00e9]]\n| writer         = [[Victor Alexandrov]]<br>[[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]<br>[[Jacques Compan\u00e9ez]]<br>[[Henri Jeanson]]<br>[[Jacques R\u00e9my (writer)|Jacques R\u00e9my]]\n| starring       = [[Henri Vidal]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Henri Alekan\n| editing        = Roger Dwyre\n| distributor    = [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont]]\n| released       = {{film date|1947|09|19|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''The Damned''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Les Maudits'''}}) is a 1947 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]].<ref>{{cite web|work=[[PopMatters]]|title=The Young Baron of 'The Damned' Was Seen Coming Out of One of Those Clubs|first=J.C.|last=Ma\u00e7ek III|date=26 August 2013|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/174623-the-damned/}}</ref> It was entered into the [[1947 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/4234/year/1947.html |title=Festival de Cannes: The Damned |accessdate=5 January 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> The film is notable for its depiction of the interior of a wartime submarine and for its tracking shots through the length of the U-boat.\n\n==Plot==\nAs Germany is in the throes of losing World War II, a number of wealthy Nazis and some French sympathizers head for South America in a German submarine leaving from Oslo. The film's narrator is a French doctor ([[Henri Vidal]]) who has been kidnapped to tend a sick woman, Hilde Garosi ([[Florence Marly]]), the wife of one man and the lover of another, both aboard. The doctor realizes he will be murdered at any point once the woman has recovered so he tries various stratagems to escape. All fail.\n\nThe mission slowly disintegrates as the war ends and its reasons for being dissipate, with some passengers either trying to escape or committing suicide. Forster ([[Jo Dest]]) tries to continue the mission even after Berlin has fallen and orders have gone out for all U-boats to surrender at the nearest port. Part of the crew finally mutinies against the insane ones still fighting the war. The doctor ends up alone on the Nazi sub for days writing his memoirs until an American ship rescues him and finally sinks his infamous abode at sea.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Marcel Dalio]] as Larga (as Dalio)\n* [[Henri Vidal]] as Docteur Guilbert\n* [[Florence Marly]] as Hilde Garosi\n* [[Fosco Giachetti]] as Garosi\n* [[Paul Bernard (actor)|Paul Bernard]] as Couturier\n* [[Jo Dest]] as Forster (as Jodest)\n* [[Michel Auclair]] as Willy Morus\n* {{ill|Anne Campion|fr}} as Ingrid Ericksen\n* [[Andreas von Halberstadt]] (as A. Von Halberstadt)\n* [[Lucien Hector]] as Ericksen\n* [[Jean Lozach]] (as Lozach)\n* [[Karl M\u00fcnch]] (as Karl Munch)\n\n==Restoration==\nIn 2013, the [[Cohen Film Collection]] released ''The Damned'' on Blu-ray and DVD in the US,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Damned|url=http://cohenmedia.net/the-damned|work=Cohenmedia.net}}</ref> using a restoration carried out by the French distributor, [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0039615}}\n\n{{Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment |state=collapsed}}\n{{Palme d'Or 1939-1959}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Damned, The}}\n[[Category:1947 films]]\n[[Category:1947 drama films]]\n[[Category:French black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ren\u00e9 Cl\u00e9ment]]\n[[Category:World War II submarine films]]\n[[Category:Palme d'Or winners]]\n"