{"title_page": "Midrasha", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2008}}\nA '''''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: {{hebrew|\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05d4}}, pl. ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot/midrashas}}'') refers to an institute of [[Torah study|Jewish studies]] for women. In [[Israel]], it is often an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] institution that caters solely to women, and roughly the equivalent of a [[yeshiva]] for men. The term is often translated as '[[seminary]]'.{{fact|date=October 2014}} \n\nIn [[Israel]], a midrasha that offers [[academic degree|degree studies]] is sometimes called a ''machon'' (institute). Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}''  accept both men and women, such as the Ein Prat Midrasha<ref>[http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html Eni Prat Midrasha Bogrim.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101012427/http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html |date=2007-11-01 }}</ref> in Israel.\n\nIn the [[United States]], the term has also been used to refer to co-educational Jewish studies programs, allowing high school students to continue their Jewish education post [[bar mitzvah|bar]] / [[bat mitzvah]].{{Citation needed}}\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word \"''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''\" is based on the term ''[[beit midrash]]'', \"house of study\".  It is [[cognate]] with the [[Arabic]] \"''{{transl|ar|[[madrasa|madrasah]]}}'',\" which also refers to a place of learning.\n\n==Structure==\n''{{lang|he-Latn|Midrashot}}'' vary in curriculum and [[Orthodox Judaism#Social and philosophic differences|philosophy]]. More liberal ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' often place more emphasis on the study of [[Talmud]] itself, as in men's {{lang|he-Latn|[[yeshiva|yeshivot]]}}, while more conservative ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' tend to only incorporate selections from the Talmud in the context of classes on the [[Tanakh|Hebrew Bible]], [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Musar Literature|Ethics (Musar)]] and [[Halacha|Jewish law]] instead. Most ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' in the latter category are modeled on the [[Beis Yaakov]] teacher-training seminary established by [[Sarah Schenirer]].\n\nMany Orthodox Jewish girls attend a ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}'' in Israel for a year or more following high school. Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' are designed for [[baal teshuva|the newly observant]].\n\nMost ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' for English-speaking students are accredited by American colleges. Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' offer second-year programs with religious-studies classes in the morning and general-studies classes in the afternoons, allowing students to pursue a religious education and a general-studies education leading to a college degree simultaneously. In Israel, several of the religious affiliated [[List_of_universities_and_colleges_in_Israel#Colleges|teacher training colleges]] also offer a religious studies program in conjunction with the [[B.Ed.]] degree.\n<!-- \n==Coed high school Midrashot==\nWhile a [[Hebrew school]] program typically handles [[Jewish education]] for youths before their [[Bar/Bat Mitzvah]], students who wish to continue their Jewish education through high school enroll in a Midrasha.\n -->\n==See also==\n* [[Beis Yaakov]]\n* [[List of Midrashot]]\n* [[Role of women in Judaism]]\n* [[Female seminary]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:Jewish educational institutions]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2008}}\nA '''''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: {{hebrew|\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05d4}}, pl. ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot/midrashas}}'') refers to an institute of [[Torah study|Jewish studies]] for women. In [[Israel]], it is often an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] institution that caters solely to women, and roughly the equivalent of a [[yeshiva]] for men. The term is often translated as '[[seminary]]'.{{fact|date=October 2014}} \n\nIn [[Israel]], a midrasha that offers [[academic degree|degree studies]] is sometimes called a ''machon'' (institute). Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}''  accept both men and women, such as the Ein Prat Midrasha<ref>[http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html Eni Prat Midrasha Bogrim.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101012427/http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html |date=2007-11-01 }}</ref> in Israel.\n\nIn the [[United States]], the term has also been used to refer to co-educational Jewish studies programs, allowing high school students to continue their Jewish education post [[bar mitzvah|bar]] / [[bat-mitzvah]].{{Citation needed}}\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word \"''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''\" is based on the term ''[[beit midrash]]'', \"house of study\".  It is [[cognate]] with the [[Arabic]] \"''{{transl|ar|[[madrasa|madrasah]]}}'',\" which also refers to a place of learning.\n\n==Structure==\n''{{lang|he-Latn|Midrashot}}'' vary in curriculum and [[Orthodox Judaism#Social and philosophic differences|philosophy]]. More liberal ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' often place more emphasis on the study of [[Talmud]] itself, as in men's {{lang|he-Latn|[[yeshiva|yeshivot]]}}, while more conservative ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' tend to only incorporate selections from the Talmud in the context of classes on the [[Tanakh|Hebrew Bible]], [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Musar Literature|Ethics (Musar)]] and [[Halacha|Jewish law]] instead. Most ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' in the latter category are modeled on the [[Beis Yaakov]] teacher-training seminary established by [[Sarah Schenirer]].\n\nMany Orthodox Jewish girls attend a ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}'' in Israel for a year or more following high school. Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' are designed for [[baal teshuva|the newly observant]].\n\nMost ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' for English-speaking students are accredited by American colleges. Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' offer second-year programs with religious-studies classes in the morning and general-studies classes in the afternoons, allowing students to pursue a religious education and a general-studies education leading to a college degree simultaneously. In Israel, several of the religious affiliated [[List_of_universities_and_colleges_in_Israel#Colleges|teacher training colleges]] also offer a religious studies program in conjunction with the [[B.Ed.]] degree.\n<!-- \n==Coed high school Midrashot==\nWhile a [[Hebrew school]] program typically handles [[Jewish education]] for youths before their [[Bar/Bat Mitzvah]], students who wish to continue their Jewish education through high school enroll in a Midrasha.\n -->\n==See also==\n* [[Beis Yaakov]]\n* [[List of Midrashot]]\n* [[Role of women in Judaism]]\n* [[Female seminary]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:Jewish educational institutions]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midrasha"}
{"title_page": "Arthur von Wartburg", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|                name = Arthur von Wartburg\n|               image =\n|            fullname = Arthur von Wartburg\n|          birth_date = 25 December 1952\n|         birth_place = \n|          death_date = \n|         death_place = \n|              height = 181cm\n|            position = [[Midfielder (football)|Midfielder]]\n|         currentclub = \n|          clubnumber = \n|         youthyears1 = until 1972\n|         youthclubs1 = [[FC Concordia Basel|Concordia Basel]]\n|              years1 = 1972\u20131973\n|              clubs1 = [[FC Concordia Basel]]\n|               caps1 = \n|              goals1 = \n|              years2 = 1973\u20131984\n|              clubs2 = [[FC Basel]]\n|               caps2 = 267\n|              goals2 = 16\n|              years3 = 1984\u20131985\n|              clubs3 = [[FC Grenchen]]\n|               caps3 = 16\n|              goals3 = 6\n|      nationalyears1 = 1976\u20131977\n|       nationalteam1 = [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]\n|       nationalcaps1 = 5\n|      nationalgoals1 = 0\n|       manageryears1 = \n|       managerclubs1 = \n|            pcupdate = \n|            ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Arthur von Wartburg''' (born 25 December 1952) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[Switzerland national football team|international]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]] who played most of his football for [[FC Basel]]. He played as [[Midfielder (football)|midfielder]].\n\n== Club career ==\nVon Wartburg played his youth football by [[FC Concordia Basel|Concordia Basel]] and advanced to their first team in 1972.\n\nVon Wartburg joined [[FC Basel|Basel]] for their [[1973\u201374 FC Basel season|1973\u201374 season]] under first team manager [[Helmut Benthaus]]. After playing in two test games, he played his domestic league debut for his new club in the home game at [[St. Jakob Stadium]] on 20 April 1974 as Basel drew 1\u20131 against [[FC St. Gallen|St. Gallen]].<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-sg 1973/74\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23453 | title = FC Basel - FC St. Gallen 1:1 (0:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his club on 7 August 1974 in the [[Swiss League Cup]] against [[FC Luzern|Luzern]] as Basel won 5\u20132. It was the teams 5th goal of the match.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-fcl-liga pokal 1974/75\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23408 | title = FC Basel - FC Luzern 5:2 (3:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nIn their [[1974\u201375 FC Basel season|1974\u201375 season]] von Wartburg scored his first domestic league goal for his club on 31 August 1974 in the home game against [[FC Winterthur|Winterthur]] as Basel won by five goals to nil.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-winterthur 1974/75\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23383 | title = FC Basel - FC Winterthur 5:0 (1:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> Von Wartburg and his team ended the championship in fourth position. But in the Swiss Cup tournament they reached the final. The final was played on 31 March 1975 also in the [[Wankdorf Stadium]] in [[Bern]] against [[FC Winterthur|Winterthur]]. [[Otto Demarmels]] scored the opening goal for Basel, Meyer equalised and so the game went into extra time. [[Walter Balmer (footballer)|Walter Balmer]] scored the winning goal for Basel after 115 minutes. Basel were Swiss Cup winners for the fifth time in the club's history.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-winterthur-fcb\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23417 | title = FC Winterthur - FC Basel 1:2 n.V. (1:1, 0:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nBasel finished the 1975\u201376 league championship in third position with 34 points, 10 points behind [[FC Z\u00fcrich]]. Of the 26 games, 13 were won, 8 drawn, 5 lost, with 59 goals and 38 conceded. Von Wartburg played 22 league games scoring three goals.\n\nFor von Wartburg the 1976\u201377 was again a very successful season. The league format was changed. Instead of 14 teams playing a single round robin, it now was reduced to 12 teams with a Qualifying phase and a championship round with the six top teams. This meant no longer 26 games, but now 22 plus 10.<ref name=\"rsssf-1977\">{{cite web | first = Erik | last = Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwithist.html#1977 | title = Switzerland Final League Tables of the Nationalliga A and B 1930-2000 | format = | work = | publisher = The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> In the Qualifying phase Basel obtained 33 points and were just two points behind [[Servette FC|Servette]]. They managed to close the gap in the championship round and because both teams were level on points the championship was decided in a play-off match. This match was held on 26 June 1977. Basel's first goals was scored by [[Walter Mundschin]] and von Wartburg scored the winning goal as they won 2\u20131 and became Swiss champions.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-servette-fcb\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23144 | title = FC Basel - Servette FC 2:1 (1:1) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> In the league von Wartburg played in 32 of the 33 matches scoring three goals.\n\nDuring the season 1977\u201378 von Wartburg played 52 games including the test games and netted three times. The team fished the championship in third position. In both the national cup competitions they reached the semi-final but lost both. Arthur von Wartburg doesn't have a very good memories of the UEFA Cup match against [[VfB Stuttgart]] on 13 September 1978. The Germans played with all their stars, [[Hansi M\u00fcller]], [[Dieter Hoeness]], [[Hermann Ohlicher]] and the F\u00f6rster brothers [[Karlheinz F\u00f6rster|Karlheinz]] and [[Bernd F\u00f6rster|Bernd]]. Basel took a 1-0 lead through [[J\u00f6rg Stohler|Stohler]]. Then in the 40th minute, the reliable thinker and driver in midfield von Wartburg was given yellow-red for some unknown reason from Referee [[Brian McGinlay]]. Von Wartburg had to leave the place prematurely. The Germans turned the game and won it 3\u20132. That was to be von Wartburg's the only dismissal in his entire career.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-vfb stuttgart 1977/78\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=21711 | title = FC Basel - VfB Stuttgart 2:3 (1:1) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> \n\nDuring the 1978\u201379 season he played 57 games including the tests and tallied again three goals. Basel ended the league season sixth position after playing a disappointing championship round, losing six of the last seven games.\n\nThe season [[1979\u201380 Nationalliga A]] was an exiting season. After the Qualifying phase [[Servette FC|Servette]], [[Grasshopper Club Z\u00fcrich|Grasshopper Club]] and Basel were within three points of each other. The close rivalry remained until the end of the season. In the second last game Basel were hosts to Servette, winning 1\u20130, and in the last away against Z\u00fcrich, winning 4\u20132. Basel became champions and were two points ahead of both Grasshoppers and Servette who fished second and third respectively.<ref name=\"rsssf-1980\">{{cite web | first = Erik | last = Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwithist.html#1980 | title = Switzerland Final League Tables of the Nationalliga A and B 1930-2000 | format = | work = | publisher = The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> The team scored 91 league goals all in all. The teams top scorers were [[Detlev Lauscher]],  [[Joseph K\u00fcttel]] and [[Erni Maissen]] each of whom scored 18 league goals during the campaign. von Wartburg scored four in 32 outings and this was his second league championship title.\n\nVon Wartburg played four further seasons for Basel. In the season 1980\u201381 he had 26 league appearances without scoring, in the 1981\u201382 season he had 30 league appearances scoring twice, in the 1982\u201383 season he played 22 league games without scoring and during the 1983\u201384 season he had 14 league appearances scoring once. \n\nBetween the years 1973 and 1984 von Wartburg played a total of 476 games for Basel scoring a total of 41 goals. 267 of these games were in the [[Swiss Super League|Nationalliga A]], 29 in the [[Swiss Cup]], 24 in the [[Swiss League Cup]], six in the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]], four in the [[UEFA Cup]], 25 in the [[Cup of the Alps]] and 121 were friendly games. He scored 16 goals in the domestic league, four were in the two cup competitions, three were in European competitions and the other 18 were scored during the test games.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-Arthur von Wartburg\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/spieler?command=detail&id=7563 | title = Arthur von Wartburg - FCB-Statistik | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nAfter his time in Basel von Wartburg moved on to [[FC Grenchen]] in the Nationalliga B (second tier of Swiss football). During this season Grenchen played 30 games, winning 15 times, drawing 10 and losing only five times. With 40 points they ended the season as Nationalliga B champions and were promoted. Von Wartburg played for Grenchen just this one season and then he ended his active football career.<ref name=\"rsssf-Switzerland 1984/85\">{{cite web | first = | last = Erik Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = |  url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit85.html | title = Switzerland 1984/85 | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\n== International career ==\nArthur von Wartburg was called up for his country in the 1976\u20131977 season. He played his debut for [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] on 23 April 1977 as they were defeated 0\u20134 by [[France national football team|France]] in a friendly game. He played four more games for his country including a\n[[1978 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 6|qualifing match to the 1978 World Cup]] on 8 June 1977 against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]].\n\n==Honours==\n;Basel\n* [[Swiss Super League|Swiss League]]: [[Swiss Super League 1976-77|1976-77]], [[Swiss Super League 1979-80|1979-80]]\n* [[Schweizer Cup|Swiss Cup]]: 1974\u201375\n* [[Cup of the Alps]] winner: 1981\n\n;Grenchen\n* Nationalliga B champions: 1984\u201385\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Rotblau: Jahrbuch Saison 2017/2018. Publisher: FC Basel Marketing AG. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2189-1}}\n* Die ersten 125 Jahre. Publisher: Josef Zindel im Friedrich Reinhardt Verlag, Basel. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2305-5}}\n* [https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/home Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\" Homepage]\n* [https://www.fcb.ch/de-CH/News/2017/09/06/Arthur-von-Wartburg-der-Inbegriff-von-Vereinstre?ext= Arthur von Wartburg on FCB Homepage]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:von Wartburg, Arthur }}\n\n[[Category:FC Basel players]]\n[[Category:FC Grenchen players]]\n[[Category:Swiss footballers]]\n[[Category:Switzerland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|                name = Arthur von Wartburg\n|               image =\n|            fullname = Arthur von Wartburg\n|          birth_date = 25 December 1952\n|         birth_place = \n|          death_date = \n|         death_place = \n|              height = 181cm\n|            position = [[Midfielder (football)|Midfielder]]\n|         currentclub = \n|          clubnumber = \n|         youthyears1 = until 1972\n|         youthclubs1 = [[FC Concordia Basel|Concordia Basel]]\n|              years1 = 1972\u20131973\n|              clubs1 = [[FC Concordia Basel]]\n|               caps1 = \n|              goals1 = \n|              years2 = 1973\u20131984\n|              clubs2 = [[FC Basel]]\n|               caps2 = 267\n|              goals2 = 16\n|              years3 = 1984\u20131985\n|              clubs3 = [[FC Grenchen]]\n|               caps3 = 16\n|              goals3 = 6\n|      nationalyears1 = 1976\u20131977\n|       nationalteam1 = [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]\n|       nationalcaps1 = 5\n|      nationalgoals1 = 0\n|       manageryears1 = \n|       managerclubs1 = \n|            pcupdate = \n|            ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Arthur von Wartburg''' (* 25 December 1952) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[Switzerland national football team|international]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]] who played most of his football for [[FC Basel]]. He played as [[Midfielder (football)|midfielder]]. \n\n== Club career ==\nVon Wartburg played his youth football by [[FC Concordia Basel|Concordia Basel]] and advanced to their first team in 1972.\n\nVon Wartburg joined [[FC Basel|Basel]] for their [[1973\u201374 FC Basel season|1973\u201374 season]] under first team manager [[Helmut Benthaus]]. After playing in two test games, he played his domestic league debut for his new club in the home game at [[St. Jakob Stadium]] on 20 April 1974 as Basel drew 1\u20131 against [[FC St. Gallen|St. Gallen]].<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-sg 1973/74\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23453 | title = FC Basel - FC St. Gallen 1:1 (0:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his club on 7 August 1974 in the [[Swiss League Cup]] against [[FC Luzern|Luzern]] as Basel won 5\u20132. It was the teams 5th goal of the match.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-fcl-liga pokal 1974/75\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23408 | title = FC Basel - FC Luzern 5:2 (3:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nIn their [[1974\u201375 FC Basel season|1974\u201375 season]] von Wartburg scored his first domestic league goal for his club on 31 August 1974 in the home game against [[FC Winterthur|Winterthur]] as Basel won by five goals to nil.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-winterthur 1974/75\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23383 | title = FC Basel - FC Winterthur 5:0 (1:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> Von Wartburg and his team ended the championship in fourth position. But in the Swiss Cup tournament they reached the final. The final was played on 31 March 1975 also in the [[Wankdorf Stadium]] in [[Bern]] against [[FC Winterthur|Winterthur]]. [[Otto Demarmels]] scored the opening goal for Basel, Meyer equalised and so the game went into extra time. [[Walter Balmer (footballer)|Walter Balmer]] scored the winning goal for Basel after 115 minutes. Basel were Swiss Cup winners for the fifth time in the club's history.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-winterthur-fcb\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23417 | title = FC Winterthur - FC Basel 1:2 n.V. (1:1, 0:0) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nBasel finished the 1975\u201376 league championship in third position with 34 points, 10 points behind [[FC Z\u00fcrich]]. Of the 26 games, 13 were won, 8 drawn, 5 lost, with 59 goals and 38 conceded. Von Wartburg played 22 league games scoring three goals.\n\nFor von Wartburg the 1976\u201377 was again a very successful season. The league format was changed. Instead of 14 teams playing a single round robin, it now was reduced to 12 teams with a Qualifying phase and a championship round with the six top teams. This meant no longer 26 games, but now 22 plus 10.<ref name=\"rsssf-1977\">{{cite web | first = Erik | last = Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwithist.html#1977 | title = Switzerland Final League Tables of the Nationalliga A and B 1930-2000 | format = | work = | publisher = The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> In the Qualifying phase Basel obtained 33 points and were just two points behind [[Servette FC|Servette]]. They managed to close the gap in the championship round and because both teams were level on points the championship was decided in a play-off match. This match was held on 26 June 1977. Basel's first goals was scored by [[Walter Mundschin]] and von Wartburg scored the winning goal as they won 2\u20131 and became Swiss champions.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-servette-fcb\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=23144 | title = FC Basel - Servette FC 2:1 (1:1) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> In the league von Wartburg played in 32 of the 33 matches scoring three goals.\n\nDuring the season 1977\u201378 von Wartburg played 52 games including the test games and netted three times. The team fished the championship in third position. In both the national cup competitions they reached the semi-final but lost both. Arthur von Wartburg doesn't have a very good memories of the UEFA Cup match against [[VfB Stuttgart]] on 13 September 1978. The Germans played with all their stars, [[Hansi M\u00fcller]], [[Dieter Hoeness]], [[Hermann Ohlicher]] and the F\u00f6rster brothers [[Karlheinz F\u00f6rster|Karlheinz]] and [[Bernd F\u00f6rster|Bernd]]. Basel took a 1-0 lead through [[J\u00f6rg Stohler|Stohler]]. Then in the 40th minute, the reliable thinker and driver in midfield von Wartburg was given yellow-red for some unknown reason from Referee [[Brian McGinlay]]. Von Wartburg had to leave the place prematurely. The Germans turned the game and won it 3\u20132. That was to be von Wartburg's the only dismissal in his entire career.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-fcb-vfb stuttgart 1977/78\">{{cite web | first = | last = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=21711 | title = FC Basel - VfB Stuttgart 2:3 (1:1) | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> \n\nDuring the 1978\u201379 season he played 57 games including the tests and tallied again three goals. Basel ended the league season sixth position after playing a disappointing championship round, losing six of the last seven games.\n\nThe season [[1979\u201380 Nationalliga A]] was an exiting season. After the Qualifying phase [[Servette FC|Servette]], [[Grasshopper Club Z\u00fcrich|Grasshopper Club]] and Basel were within three points of each other. The close rivalry remained until the end of the season. In the second last game Basel were hosts to Servette, winning 1\u20130, and in the last away against Z\u00fcrich, winning 4\u20132. Basel became champions and were two points ahead of both Grasshoppers and Servette who fished second and third respectively.<ref name=\"rsssf-1980\">{{cite web | first = Erik | last = Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwithist.html#1980 | title = Switzerland Final League Tables of the Nationalliga A and B 1930-2000 | format = | work = | publisher = The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation. | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref> The team scored 91 league goals all in all. The teams top scorers were [[Detlev Lauscher]],  [[Joseph K\u00fcttel]] and [[Erni Maissen]] each of whom scored 18 league goals during the campaign. von Wartburg scored four in 32 outings and this was his second league championship title.\n\nVon Wartburg played four further seasons for Basel. In the season 1980\u201381 he had 26 league appearances without scoring, in the 1981\u201382 season he had 30 league appearances scoring twice, in the 1982\u201383 season he played 22 league games without scoring and during the 1983\u201384 season he had 14 league appearances scoring once. \n\nBetween the years 1973 and 1984 von Wartburg played a total of 476 games for Basel scoring a total of 41 goals. 267 of these games were in the [[Swiss Super League|Nationalliga A]], 29 in the [[Swiss Cup]], 24 in the [[Swiss League Cup]], six in the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]], four in the [[UEFA Cup]], 25 in the [[Cup of the Alps]] and 121 were friendly games. He scored 16 goals in the domestic league, four were in the two cup competitions, three were in European competitions and the other 18 were scored during the test games.<ref name=\"fcb-achiv-Arthur von Wartburg\">{{cite web | first = | last = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/spieler?command=detail&id=7563 | title = Arthur von Wartburg - FCB-Statistik | format = | work = | publisher = Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\u201d | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nAfter his time in Basel von Wartburg moved on to [[FC Grenchen]] in the Nationalliga B (second tier of Swiss football). During this season Grenchen played 30 games, winning 15 times, drawing 10 and losing only five times. With 40 points they ended the season as Nationalliga B champions and were promoted. Von Wartburg played for Grenchen just this one season and then he ended his active football career.<ref name=\"rsssf-Switzerland 1984/85\">{{cite web | first = | last = Erik Garin | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = |  url = http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit85.html | title = Switzerland 1984/85 | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate = 2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\n== International career ==\nArthur von Wartburg was called up for his country in the 1976\u20131977 season. He played his debut for [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] on 23 April 1977 as they were defeated 0\u20134 by [[France national football team|France]] in a friendly game. He played four more games for his country including a\n[[1978 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 6|qualifing match to the 1978 World Cup]] on 8 June 1977 against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]].\n\n==Honours==\n;Basel\n* [[Swiss Super League|Swiss League]]: [[Swiss Super League 1976-77|1976-77]], [[Swiss Super League 1979-80|1979-80]]\n* [[Schweizer Cup|Swiss Cup]]: 1974\u201375\n* [[Cup of the Alps]] winner: 1981\n\n;Grenchen\n* Nationalliga B champions: 1984\u201385\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Rotblau: Jahrbuch Saison 2017/2018. Publisher: FC Basel Marketing AG. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2189-1}}\n* Die ersten 125 Jahre. Publisher: Josef Zindel im Friedrich Reinhardt Verlag, Basel. {{ISBN|978-3-7245-2305-5}}\n* [https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/home Verein \"Basler Fussballarchiv\" Homepage]\n* [https://www.fcb.ch/de-CH/News/2017/09/06/Arthur-von-Wartburg-der-Inbegriff-von-Vereinstre?ext= Arthur von Wartburg on FCB Homepage]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:von Wartburg, Arthur }}\n\n[[Category:FC Basel players]]\n[[Category:FC Grenchen players]]\n[[Category:Swiss footballers]]\n[[Category:Switzerland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_von_Wartburg"}
